{"title_page": "Leon Restaurants", "text_new": "{{short description|British fast food chain}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{COI|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Leon Restaurants Limited\n| logo = Leon Restaurants.svg\n| caption = \n| type = [[Private Company|Private]]\n| genre = Fast food\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = 2004<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leon.co/vision|title=Vision}}</ref>\n| founders = [[John Vincent (restaurateur)|John Vincent]]<br>[[Henry Dimbleby]]<br>[[Allegra McEvedy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leon.co/founders|title=Founders}}</ref>\n| defunct = \n| location_city = London\n| location_country = United Kingdom\n| location = \n| locations = 61 (March 2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leon.co/restaurants|title=Restaurants}}</ref>\n| area_served = United Kingdom, Ireland, Netherlands, Norway, Spain, United States\n| key_people = [[John Vincent (restaurateur)|John Vincent]], Chief Executive Officer\n| industry = [[Restaurant]]\n| products = \n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = https://leon.co/\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n\n[[File:Kingsx-6119.jpg|thumb|Leon, Kings Cross Station, London]]\n\n'''Leon''' (branded as '''LEON'''.) is a [[fast food restaurant]] chain based in the United Kingdom, established in 2004.\n\n==History==\n''Leon'' was founded by [[John Vincent (restaurateur) |John Vincent]] and [[Henry Dimbleby]] with chef [[Allegra McEvedy]].<ref name=\"Dimbleby1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/henry-dimbleby-nine-restaurants-and-growing-1772726.html|title=Henry Dimbleby: nine restaurants and growing|date=16 August 2009|work=[[The Independent]] |author= Evans, Simon|accessdate=23 September 2012 | location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"Vincent\">{{cite web | url=http://www.marketingmagazine.co.uk/article/1213217/john-vincent-co-founder-leon-restaurants | title=John Vincent, co-founder, Leon Restaurants | work=Marketing | date=25 September 2013 | accessdate=5 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thegatewayonline.com/articles/food/leon|title=If God owned McDonald's...|author1=Bordell, Tom|author2=Jaffer, Mehdi|publisher=The Gateway|accessdate=23 September 2012|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026014112/http://thegatewayonline.com/articles/food/leon|archive-date=26 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/food/chefs/allegra_mcevedy|title=Food chefs: Allegra McEvedy|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=23 September 2012| location=London}}</ref> The business was named after Vincent's father, Leon,<ref name = Dimbleby2>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/henry-dimbleby-nine-restaurants-and-growing-1772726.html|title=Henry Dimbleby: nine restaurants and growing|work=[[The Independent]] |date= 16 August 2009|author= Evans, Simon|accessdate=23 September 2012 | location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"Vincent\"/><ref name=\"Director\">{{cite news|url=http://www.director.co.uk/magazine/2008/7%20July/leon_61_12.html|title=Profile: Leon|last=Nielsen|first=Tina|date=July 2008|work=Director magazine|accessdate=8 January 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121212246/http://www.director.co.uk/magazine/2008/7%20July/leon_61_12.html|archive-date=21 November 2008|location=London}}</ref> and opened its first outlet in [[Carnaby Street]] in 2004.<ref name=\"Saskia Leon\">{{cite web|last1=Restaurants|first1=Leon|title=Vision|url=http://leonrestaurants.co.uk/vision/|website=Leonrestaurants.co.uk|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/food-and-drink/features/fast-food-neednt-be-junk-food-523835.html|title=Fast food needn't be junk food|last=Scott-Moncrieff|first=Chloe|date=22 January 2006|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=23 September 2012  | location=London}}</ref> Six months after opening, ''Leon'' was named the \"Best New Restaurant in Great Britain\" at [[The Observer#21st century|''The Observer Food Monthly'' Awards]].<ref name= Director/> \n\nIn March 2009, McEvedy gave up her role at ''Leon'' to focus on writing and television work, but remains a shareholder. In 2014, John Vincent took over from Henry Dimbleby as CEO, and Dimbleby then left the board in 2017. He also remains a shareholder. ''Leon'' is backed by Active Private Equity and, in May 2017, Spice Private Equity became a major investor to support further global expansion plans.\n\n==Restaurants==\nBy 2015 ''Leon'' had 57 restaurants,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://leonrestaurants.co.uk/restaurants/|title=Restaurants \u2013 Leon Restaurants|website=Leonrestaurants.co.uk|accessdate=15 October 2015}}</ref> and in June 2016 the first ''Leon'' outside England opened in [[Amsterdam]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/05/08/healthy-fast-food-chain-leon-reveals-profit-leap---and-its-secre/|title=Healthy fast food chain Leon reveals profit leap \u2013 and its secret martial arts experiment|website=The Telegraph|access-date=13 June 2016}}</ref> Other international openings followed including restaurants at Utrecht, Oslo, Gran Canaria, Dublin and ''Leon's'' first restaurant in the United States, in [[Washington D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/business/leon-aims-to-help-us-fall-back-in-love-with-fast-food-a3871116.html|title=Leon aims to help US \u2018fall back in love\u2019 with fast food|date=25 June 2018|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> In 2018, the company had 61 sites.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn January 2015, HMSHost operated six ''Leon'' locations in airports and railway stations in southern England, and ''Leon'' announced an expansion of its relationship with HMSHost in 2018, including a franchise agreement in airports and railway stations across Europe and the Middle East.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Restaurants|first1=Leon|title=HMS|url=http://leonrestaurants.co.uk/hms/|publisher=Leonrestaurants.co.uk|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Central & East News|title=Leon Lands at Stansted|url=http://www.insidermedia.com/insider/central-and-east/130197-leon-lands-london-stansted/|publisher=insidermedia.com|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lysecki|first1=Sarah|title=HMSHost wins Eurotunnel and East Midlands Airport concessions|url=http://www.moodiereport.com/document.php?doc_id=37073|website=Moodiereport.com|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref> By establishing this presence, the company hoped to reach an international audience, and help create demand ahead of further overseas openings.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burn-Callander|first1=Rebecca|title=Leon eyes US expansion|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/10870557/Leon-eyes-US-expansion-from-Heathrow-base.html|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://qsrmedia.co.uk/international/news/leon-launches-flagship-restaurant-in-gran-canaria-airport|title=LEON launches flagship restaurant in Gran Canaria Airport|website=QSRMedia UK|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, ''Leon'' became a founding member of the Sustainable Restaurant Association, and won Raymond Blanc's Sustainability Hero award at the Association's \"Food Made Good\" Awards. The chain was named in the 2017 ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' Fast Track 100.\n\n== Other activities ==\n''Leon'' has published several cookbooks, and developed a cookware and tableware line with retailer [[John Lewis (department store)|John Lewis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.com/lifestyle/20121017/english-restaurateurs-share-ideas-for-healthy-cooking-in-leon-naturally-fast-food|title=English restaurateurs share ideas for healthy cooking in \u2018Leon: Naturally Fast Food\u2019|date=17 October 2012|publisher=|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.johnlewis.com/brand/leon/_/N-1z08x2u|title=LEON - John Lewis & Partners|website=www.johnlewis.com|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Wing Tsun==\n''Leon'' co-founder and CEO, John Vincent, has co-authored a book, 'Winning Not Fighting' with Sifu Julian Hitch, to be published in November 2019. The book takes the principles of the ancient martial art of [[Wing Chun|Wing Tsun]] and applies them to achieving success in work, life and business.<ref name=WT>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/306/306457/winning-not-fighting/9780241318379.html|title=Winning Not Fighting|authors=Vincent, John; Hitch, Julian|publisher = [[Penguin Books]]|language=en|access-date=16 August 2019}}</ref> It encourages readers not to conceive of business as a battle \u2013 a core principle of Wing Tsun is that fighting should be avoided at all costs. \n\nVincent has revealed that Wing Tsun shapes the way that ''Leon'' operates. All new employees at ''Leon'' are put through Wing Tsun training and Vincent claims that this has improved the speed and quality of ''Leon'' baristas' coffee-making.<ref name=WT/>\n\n== Policies ==\nIn the United Kingdom, ''Leon'' implements equal pay, for both age and gender. The company pays the over 25s rate of the [[National Living Wage]] to all hourly paid employees, including those aged below 25.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/05018441/filing-history/MzIzNDIwMDA4MmFkaXF6a2N4/document?format=pdf&download=0|title=Leon Restaurants Limited: Annual Report and Financial Statements, 2018|last=|first=|date=|publisher=[[Companies House]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the first quarter of 2019, 53% of the chain's food sales were plant-based or vegetarian.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Feed NHS ==\nIn March 2020, ''Leon'' set up the 'Feed NHS' initiative to deliver 5,600 free meals a day to [[National Health Service|NHS]] [[intensive care medicine|critical care]] staff at London hospitals during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Butler|first=Sarah|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/27/leon-sets-up-initiative-to-deliver-free-hot-meals-to-nhs-staff-coronavirus|title=Leon sets up initiative to deliver free meals to NHS critical care staff|date=2020-03-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Other [[Chain_store#Restaurant_chains|restaurant chains]] joined the initiative, including: ''[[Franco Manca]]'', ''[[Tortilla (restaurant chain)|Tortilla]]'', and ''[[Wasabi (restaurant)|Wasabi]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecaterer.com/news/leon-feed-nhs-campaign|title=These amazing people need us - Leon's FeedNHS appeal for 'vital funds' hopes to raise \u00a31m|last=Milsom|first=Jennie|date=2020-03-27|website=The Caterer|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> A [[JustGiving]] page was created to raise funds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.justgiving.com/crowdfunding/FeedNHS?utm_term=73NP5kKnE|title=Damian, Helen & Matt|last=|first=|date=|website=JustGiving|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{UK Food}}\n\n[[Category:Restaurants established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Restaurant groups in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in London]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:British brands]]\n[[Category:Fast-food chains of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British fast food chain}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{COI|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Leon Restaurants Limited\n| logo = Leon Restaurants.svg\n| caption = \n| type = [[Private Company|Private]]\n| genre = Fast food\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = 2004<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leon.co/vision|title=Vision}}</ref>\n| founders = [[John Vincent (restaurateur)|John Vincent]]<br>[[Henry Dimbleby]]<br>[[Allegra McEvedy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leon.co/founders|title=Founders}}</ref>\n| defunct = \n| location_city = London\n| location_country = United Kingdom\n| location = \n| locations = 61 (March 2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leon.co/restaurants|title=Restaurants}}</ref>\n| area_served = United Kingdom, Ireland, Netherlands, Norway, Spain, United States\n| key_people = [[John Vincent (restaurateur)|John Vincent]], Chief Executive Officer\n| industry = [[Restaurant]]\n| products = \n| services = \n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| aum = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| homepage = https://leon.co/\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n}}\n\n[[File:Kingsx-6119.jpg|thumb|Leon, Kings Cross Station, London]]\n\n'''Leon''' (branded as '''LEON'''.) is a [[fast food restaurant]] chain based in the United Kingdom, established in 2004.\n\n==History==\n''Leon'' was founded by [[John Vincent (restaurateur) |John Vincent]] and [[Henry Dimbleby]] with chef [[Allegra McEvedy]].<ref name=\"Dimbleby1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/henry-dimbleby-nine-restaurants-and-growing-1772726.html|title=Henry Dimbleby: nine restaurants and growing|date=16 August 2009|work=[[The Independent]] |author= Evans, Simon|accessdate=23 September 2012 | location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"Vincent\">{{cite web | url=http://www.marketingmagazine.co.uk/article/1213217/john-vincent-co-founder-leon-restaurants | title=John Vincent, co-founder, Leon Restaurants | work=Marketing | date=25 September 2013 | accessdate=5 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thegatewayonline.com/articles/food/leon|title=If God owned McDonald's...|author1=Bordell, Tom|author2=Jaffer, Mehdi|publisher=The Gateway|accessdate=23 September 2012|location=London|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026014112/http://thegatewayonline.com/articles/food/leon|archive-date=26 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/food/chefs/allegra_mcevedy|title=Food chefs: Allegra McEvedy|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=23 September 2012| location=London}}</ref> The business was named after Vincent's father, Leon,<ref name = Dimbleby2>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/analysis-and-features/henry-dimbleby-nine-restaurants-and-growing-1772726.html|title=Henry Dimbleby: nine restaurants and growing|work=[[The Independent]] |date= 16 August 2009|author= Evans, Simon|accessdate=23 September 2012 | location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"Vincent\"/><ref name=\"Director\">{{cite news|url=http://www.director.co.uk/magazine/2008/7%20July/leon_61_12.html|title=Profile: Leon|last=Nielsen|first=Tina|date=July 2008|work=Director magazine|accessdate=8 January 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121212246/http://www.director.co.uk/magazine/2008/7%20July/leon_61_12.html|archive-date=21 November 2008|location=London}}</ref> and opened its first outlet in [[Carnaby Street]] in 2004.<ref name=\"Saskia Leon\">{{cite web|last1=Restaurants|first1=Leon|title=Vision|url=http://leonrestaurants.co.uk/vision/|website=Leonrestaurants.co.uk|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/food-and-drink/features/fast-food-neednt-be-junk-food-523835.html|title=Fast food needn't be junk food|last=Scott-Moncrieff|first=Chloe|date=22 January 2006|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=23 September 2012  | location=London}}</ref> Six months after opening, ''Leon'' was named the \"Best New Restaurant in Great Britain\" at [[The Observer#21st century|''The Observer Food Monthly'' Awards]].<ref name= Director/> \n\nIn March 2009, McEvedy gave up her role at ''Leon'' to focus on writing and television work, but remains a shareholder. In 2014, John Vincent took over from Henry Dimbleby as CEO, and Dimbleby then left the board in 2017. He also remains a shareholder. ''Leon'' is backed by Active Private Equity and, in May 2017, Spice Private Equity became a major investor to support further global expansion plans.\n\n==Restaurants==\nBy 2015 ''Leon'' had 57 restaurants,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://leonrestaurants.co.uk/restaurants/|title=Restaurants \u2013 Leon Restaurants|website=Leonrestaurants.co.uk|accessdate=15 October 2015}}</ref> and in June 2016 the first ''Leon'' outside England opened in [[Amsterdam]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/05/08/healthy-fast-food-chain-leon-reveals-profit-leap---and-its-secre/|title=Healthy fast food chain Leon reveals profit leap \u2013 and its secret martial arts experiment|website=The Telegraph|access-date=13 June 2016}}</ref> Other international openings followed including restaurants at Utrecht, Oslo, Gran Canaria, Dublin and ''Leon's'' first restaurant in the United States, in [[Washington D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/business/leon-aims-to-help-us-fall-back-in-love-with-fast-food-a3871116.html|title=Leon aims to help US \u2018fall back in love\u2019 with fast food|date=25 June 2018|website=Evening Standard|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> In 2018, the company had 61 sites.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn January 2015, HMSHost operated six ''Leon'' locations in airports and railway stations in southern England, and ''Leon'' announced an expansion of its relationship with HMSHost in 2018, including a franchise agreement in airports and railway stations across Europe and the Middle East.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Restaurants|first1=Leon|title=HMS|url=http://leonrestaurants.co.uk/hms/|publisher=Leonrestaurants.co.uk|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Central & East News|title=Leon Lands at Stansted|url=http://www.insidermedia.com/insider/central-and-east/130197-leon-lands-london-stansted/|publisher=insidermedia.com|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lysecki|first1=Sarah|title=HMSHost wins Eurotunnel and East Midlands Airport concessions|url=http://www.moodiereport.com/document.php?doc_id=37073|website=Moodiereport.com|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref> By establishing this presence, the company hoped to reach an international audience, and help create demand ahead of further overseas openings.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burn-Callander|first1=Rebecca|title=Leon eyes US expansion|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/10870557/Leon-eyes-US-expansion-from-Heathrow-base.html|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://qsrmedia.co.uk/international/news/leon-launches-flagship-restaurant-in-gran-canaria-airport|title=LEON launches flagship restaurant in Gran Canaria Airport|website=QSRMedia UK|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, ''Leon'' became a founding member of the Sustainable Restaurant Association, and won Raymond Blanc's Sustainability Hero award at the Association's \"Food Made Good\" Awards. The chain was named in the 2017 ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' Fast Track 100.\n\n== Other activities ==\n''Leon'' has published several cookbooks, and developed a cookware and tableware line with retailer [[John Lewis (department store)|John Lewis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.com/lifestyle/20121017/english-restaurateurs-share-ideas-for-healthy-cooking-in-leon-naturally-fast-food|title=English restaurateurs share ideas for healthy cooking in \u2018Leon: Naturally Fast Food\u2019|date=17 October 2012|publisher=|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.johnlewis.com/brand/leon/_/N-1z08x2u|title=LEON - John Lewis & Partners|website=www.johnlewis.com|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Wing Tsun==\n''Leon'' co-founder and CEO, John Vincent, has co-authored a book, 'Winning Not Fighting' with Sifu Julian Hitch, to be published in November 2019. The book takes the principles of the ancient martial art of [[Wing Chun|Wing Tsun]] and applies them to achieving success in work, life and business.<ref name=WT>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/306/306457/winning-not-fighting/9780241318379.html|title=Winning Not Fighting|authors=Vincent, John; Hitch, Julian|publisher = [[Penguin Books]]|language=en|access-date=16 August 2019}}</ref> It encourages readers not to conceive of business as a battle \u2013 a core principle of Wing Tsun is that fighting should be avoided at all costs. \n\nVincent has revealed that Wing Tsun shapes the way that ''Leon'' operates. All new employees at ''Leon'' are put through Wing Tsun training and Vincent claims that this has improved the speed and quality of ''Leon'' baristas' coffee-making.<ref name=WT/>\n\n== Policies ==\nIn the United Kingdom, ''Leon'' implements equal pay, for both age and gender. The company pays the over 25s rate of the [[National Living Wage]] to all hourly paid employees, including those aged below 25.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/05018441/filing-history/MzIzNDIwMDA4MmFkaXF6a2N4/document?format=pdf&download=0|title=Leon Restaurants Limited: Annual Report and Financial Statements, 2018|last=|first=|date=|publisher=[[Companies House]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the first quarter of 2019, 53% of the chain's food sales were plant-based or vegetarian.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Feed NHS ==\nIn March 2020, ''Leon'' set up the \"Feed NHS\" initiative to deliver 5,600 free meals a day to [[National Health Service|NHS]] [[intensive care medicine|critical care]] staff at London hospitals during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Butler|first=Sarah|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/27/leon-sets-up-initiative-to-deliver-free-hot-meals-to-nhs-staff-coronavirus|title=Leon sets up initiative to deliver free meals to NHS critical care staff|date=2020-03-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Other [[Chain_store#Restaurant_chains|restaurant chains]] became involved, including [[Franco Manca]], [[Tortilla (restaurant chain)|Tortilla]], and [[Wasabi (restaurant)|Wasabi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecaterer.com/news/leon-feed-nhs-campaign|title=These amazing people need us - Leon's FeedNHS appeal for 'vital funds' hopes to raise \u00a31m|last=Milsom|first=Jennie|date=2020-03-27|website=The Caterer|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> A [[JustGiving]] page was created to raise funds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.justgiving.com/crowdfunding/FeedNHS?utm_term=73NP5kKnE|title=Damian, Helen & Matt|last=|first=|date=|website=JustGiving|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{UK Food}}\n\n[[Category:Restaurants established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Restaurant groups in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in London]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:British brands]]\n[[Category:Fast-food chains of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Quick service restaurant", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFeed NHS)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leon_Restaurants"}
{"title_page": "Question Time (TV programme)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Question Time\n| image                    = BBC Question Time.png\n| caption                  = \n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = [[News#Newsworthiness|Topical]] [[debate]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006t1q9|title=Question Time genre}}</ref>\n| creator                  = \n| director                 = Rob Hopkin<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0by97hj|title=Rob Hopkin: Question Time Director}}</ref>\n| developer                = \n| presenter                = {{Nowrap|'''Current:'''<br>[[Fiona Bruce]] (2019\u2013)<br>'''Former:'''<br>[[Robin Day|Sir Robin Day]] (1979\u20131989)<br>[[Peter Sissons]] (1989\u20131993)<br>[[David Dimbleby]] (1994\u20132018)}}\n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = [[United Kingdom]]\n| language                 = [[English language|English]]\n| executive_producer       = [[Nicolai Gentchev]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0by97hj|title=Nicolai Gentchev: Question Time Executive Producer}}</ref>\n| producer                 = \n| editor                   = Hilary O'Neill<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0by97hj|title=Hilary O'Neill: Question Time Editor}}</ref>\n| location                 = [[location shooting|On location]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5vyK2GwYrdQGFvCJyKNfZhn/join-the-question-time-audience/contact|title=Question Time filming locations}}</ref><br>[[Question Time (TV programme)#Locations|(list of locations)]]\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 60 minutes\n| company                  = [[Brian Lapping Productions]] (previously)<br>[[Tinopolis|Mentorn Media]] (currently)\n| channel                  = [[BBC One]]\n| picture_format           = [[576i]] ([[16:9]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])<br>[[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format.            = \n| first_run                = \n| first_aired              = {{Start date|1979|9|25|df=yes}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| num_episodes             = 1,442<br>(2 April 2020)<br>\n| list_episodes            = List of Question Time episodes\n| related                  = ''[[Any Answers?]]''<br>''[[Any Questions?]]''<br>''[[The Big Questions]]''<br>''[[Dateline London]]''<br>''[[HARDtalk]]''<br>''[[Newsnight]]''<br>''Question Time Extra Time''\n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/questiontime\n| website_title            = ''Question Time''\n| production_website       = http://www.mentorn.tv/programmes/programme-list/question-time\n| production_website_title = ''Mentorn Media''\n}}\n\n'''''Question Time''''' is a [[News#Newsworthiness|topical]] [[debate]] programme, typically broadcast on [[BBC One]] at 10:35 pm on Thursdays.  It is usually repeated on [[BBC Two]] and on [[BBC Parliament]], later in the week.  ''Question Time'' is also available on [[BBC iPlayer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0003227|title=Question Time broadcast times|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episodes/b006t1q9|title=Question Time available on BBC iPlayer|website=BBC}}</ref> [[Fiona Bruce]] currently [[Chairperson|chairs]] the show having succeeded [[David Dimbleby]] as presenter in January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0by97hj|title=Fiona Bruce presents her first Question Time|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n[[Tinopolis|Mentorn]] has [[production company|produced]] the programme since 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2007/03_march/08/question.shtml|title=Press Office - Mentorn wins back Question Time contract|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Origins==\n''Question Time'' was first broadcast on Tuesday 25 September 1979, based on the [[BBC Radio 4]] programme ''[[Any Questions?]]''. The first panel consisted of [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] [[Michael Foot]], author [[Edna O'Brien]], [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician [[Teddy Taylor]], and the [[Archbishop of Liverpool]] [[Derek Worlock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/8220219.stm|title=In pictures: 30 years of Question Time|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\n''Question Time'' panels are typically composed of five public figures, \"nearly always [including] a representative from the [[Government of the United Kingdom|UK government]] and the [[Official Opposition Shadow Cabinet (United Kingdom)|official opposition]].\" The panel also features \"representatives from other [[political party|political parties]] across the series, taking as [the] guide the level of electoral support at national level which each party enjoys.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5HrMm77Yz7vwzCZZ570nTdp/frequently-asked-questions|title=Composition of Question Time panels|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nHigh-profile [[journalist]]s and [[author]]s, [[television presenter|television]] and [[radio personality|radio broadcasters]], and [[comedian]]s, join the panel, as do [[senior management|business leaders]] from well-known companies, and [[credential|leading]] or [[expert]] [[academic personnel|academics]], [[lawyer]]s, [[police officer]]s, and [[clergy|clerics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006t1q9/episodes/guide|title=Question Time panels|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n[[Audience]] members are selected by the 'audience producer' (Alison Fuller<ref>https://www.thecanary.co/uk/news/2019/05/20/snp-deputy-blasts-bbc-question-time-for-audience-stuffed-full-of-tory-plants/</ref>) based on age, [[gender]], [[job|occupation]], [[ethnic group|ethnicity]], [[disability|disability status]], voting intention, voting history, and party membership.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/send/u21723349?ptrt=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006t1q9|title=Question Time audience selection process|website=BBC}}</ref> The audience members are \"requested to come up with two questions, to be considered for the programme.\" The panel hears the questions for the first time, when the audience members ask them. Applicants are contacted on the Monday, Tuesday, or Wednesday before the programme.  Although, due to a \"[[popularity|high volume of requests]],\" the team are unable to call everyone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/send/u21723349?ptrt=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006t1q9|title=Question Time audience|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n''Question Time'' is usually recorded \"as-live\", and in a [[Take#Single-takes|single-take]], shortly before transmission. The programme is only edited on \"very rare\" occasions for [[law|legal]] or [[taste (sociology)|taste]] reasons, or because it over-runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5HrMm77Yz7vwzCZZ570nTdp/frequently-asked-questions|title=Question Time recordings|website=BBC}}</ref> For example, ''[[The Observer]]'' newspaper reported in 1986 that \"The BBC's lawyers ordered nine seconds of ''Question Time'' to be deleted by the old-fashioned method of simply cutting off the sound\".<ref>'\"High Tech, low tech, no tech\"'', The Observer,'' 9 February 1986</ref>\n\n==Presenters==\n===Sir Robin Day===\nVeteran broadcaster [[Robin Day|Sir Robin Day]] was the programme's first [[chairman|chair]], presenting it for nearly 10 years until June 1989. ''Question Time'' soon gained [[popularity]] under Day's lead, with his quick [[wit]] and [[interrogation]] skills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/talking_point/870169.stm|title=Your tributes to Sir Robin Day|website=BBC}}</ref> His famous [[catchphrase]] when he had introduced the panel was: \"There they are, and here we go.\"<ref name=\"30 Years of Question Time\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/8220219.stm|title=30 Years of Question Time|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nThe programme was mainly filmed at the Greenwood Theatre in London on the south side of [[London Bridge]]. Day's last appearance as presenter was broadcast from [[Paris]] on 12 July 1989. He was allowed to choose his own guests.<ref name=\"Sissons 2012\"/>\n\n===Peter Sissons===\n{{multiple image\n|align     = right\n|direction = vertical\n|image1    = Barbican Silk Street - geograph.org.uk - 978.jpg\n|width1    = 250\n|caption1  = [[Barbican Centre|The Barbican Centre]]\n}}\nAfter [[Robin Day|Day]] retired, [[Peter Sissons]] took over and continued until 1993. The [[BBC]] decided to widen the programme's appeal by [[location shooting|moving it around the country]]. The programme also changed its London location from the Greenwood Theatre to the [[Barbican Centre]]. Sissons' tenure as ''Question Time'' chair included three different editors. There were several problems during filming, including a [[bomb threat|bomb scare]] during a live recording, which resulted in the programme being taken off the air, and the [[death]] of an audience member who [[collapse (medical)|collapsed]] while recording.<ref name=\"Sissons 2012\">{{cite book|last=Sissons|first=Peter|title=When One Door Closes|year=2012|publisher=Biteback|isbn=978-1-84954-075-9}}</ref>\n\nThe programme continued to enjoy good ratings during this period, notably on the day of [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s resignation on 22 November 1990, which featured two different panels over two editions.<ref name=\"Sissons 2012\"/>\n\nOn 1 October 2019, Sissons' agent announced the former BBC and ITN newsreader and ''Question Time'' host died peacefully at the age of 77, with tributes paid by fellow journalists, and director-general [[Tony Hall, Baron Hall of Birkenhead|Tony Hall]].\n\n===David Dimbleby===\n[[David Dimbleby]] succeeded Sissons as ''Question Time'' presenter in 1994, after the BBC held two pilot show [[audition]]s between Dimbleby and [[Jeremy Paxman]], with two different [[audience]]s and two different panels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/dimbleby-provides-answer-for-question-time-1466997.html |title=Dimbleby provides answer for 'Question Time'|work=The Independent |date=12 December 1993 |accessdate=7 September 2014 }}</ref> For a brief period under Dimbleby in the mid-1990s, there were a number of variations to the format, including the audience using voting keypads to take a poll of the audience at the end of the programme and Dimbleby getting out of his seat at intervals to question the audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/first-night-sure-footwork-from-dimbleby-question-time-bbc-television-1406768.html |title=First Night: Sure footwork from Dimbleby: 'Question Time', BBC Television |work=The Independent |date=14 January 1994 |accessdate=7 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nDimbleby presented ''Question Time'' for 25 years, the programme's longest-serving presenter, until his final programme, aged 80, on 13 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/tv-radio/david-dimbleby-question-time-last-episode-tonight-bbc-fiona-bruce-brexit-theresa-may-vote-a8681316.html |title=David Dimbleby to host his final ever episode of Question Time tonight |newspaper=The Independent |date=13 December 2018  |author=Anu Shukla}}</ref>\n\n===Fiona Bruce===\nIn December 2018, the BBC announced that [[Fiona Bruce]] would succeed Dimbleby as [[discussion moderator|moderator]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2018/fiona-bruce-question-time|title=Fiona Bruce announced as new Question Time presenter |date=7 December 2018 |access-date=7 December 2018|website=BBC}}</ref> Bruce\u2014along with [[Samira Ahmed]], [[Victoria Derbyshire]], [[Emily Maitlis]], [[Nick Robinson (journalist)|Nick Robinson]], and [[Kirsty Wark]]\u2014attended October 2018 [[audition]]s at London's [[James Allen's Girls' School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/oct/08/emily-maitlis-and-nick-robinson-audition-in-question-time-pilots|title=Ahmed, Maitlis, Robinson, and Wark audition for Question Time role|website=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/oct/09/victoria-derbyshire-and-fiona-bruce-filmed-for-question-time-job-bbc-auditions-david-dimbleby|title=Bruce and Derbyshire audition for Question Time role|website=The Guardian}}</ref> She presented her first ''Question Time'' in January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-politics-46833072/question-time-fiona-bruce-s-debut-proves-popular|title=Praise for Fiona Bruce's first Question Time|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=11 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Guest presenters===\n''Question Time'' has seen various presenters deputise for the main chair. [[Ludovic Kennedy|Sir Ludovic Kennedy]], [[Sue Lawley]], [[Bernard Levin]], and [[Donald MacCormick]], all [[discussion moderator|moderated]] in Day's place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?adv=0&q=Question+Time+with+Ludovic+Kennedy&media=all&yf=1923&yt=2009&mf=1&mt=12&tf=00%3A00&tt=00%3A00#search|title=Sir Ludovic Kennedy presents in place of Day|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?adv=0&q=Question+Time+with+Sue+Lawley&media=all&yf=1923&yt=2009&mf=1&mt=12&tf=00%3A00&tt=00%3A00#search|title=Sue Lawley holds Day's fort|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?adv=0&q=Question+Time+with+Bernard+Levin&media=all&yf=1923&yt=2009&mf=1&mt=12&tf=00%3A00&tt=00%3A00#search|title=Bernard Levin deputises for Day|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?adv=0&q=Question+Time+with+Donald+MacCormick&media=all&yf=1923&yt=2009&mf=1&mt=12&tf=00%3A00&tt=00%3A00#search|title=Donald MacCormick in lieu of Day|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, [[John Humphrys]] presented in lieu of Dimbleby, who had been \"injured by a bullock at his farm\" causing him \"briefly to be knocked out.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8356943.stm|title=John Humphrys presents in lieu of Dimbleby|website=BBC}}</ref> In June 2017, [[Nick Robinson (journalist)|Nick Robinson]] presented a \"Leaders Special\" edition of ''Question Time''.  The programme was moved for news coverage of the [[2017 London Bridge attack|London Bridge attack]].  Dimbleby was preparing for the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|General Election coverage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08tj1sg|title=Nick Robinson presents Question Time Leaders Special|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Editors==\nCharlie Courtauld was editor from 1998 to 2000, leaving to join the ''[[Independent on Sunday]]'' as its comment editor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linkedin.com/pub/charlie-courtauld/11/b9/940|title =LinkedIn|website=LinkedIn}}</ref><ref name=Collins>{{cite news |first=Nick |last=Collins |title=Question Time's previous editors |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/8375253/Question-Times-previous-editors.html |location = London |work=Daily Telegraph |date=11 March 2011 }}</ref> [[Nick Pisani]] was appointed in 2000, resigning abruptly in May 2005 after news was leaked that he had been offered a job as David Cameron's head of TV presentation.<ref name=Collins />Ed Havard was made acting editor in May 2005 after Pisani left. During his time in charge the BBC offered a seat on the panel to Nick Griffin in 2009. He left when the programme's production base moved to Glasgow.<ref name=Collins />\n\nGill Penlington, the ITV News political producer, was made interim editor in May 2008, when the BBC gave Ed Havard a year-long sabbatical.<ref name=Collins />\n\n==Interactivity==\n\n===SMS contributions===\nViewers of the show can submit comments to the show via [[Short Message Service|SMS]]; until October 2012 a selection of those comments was posted on [[Ceefax]]. Comments were edited and put to air by a team of four journalists based at Television Centre in London. The system displayed one message at a time, and usually showed several tens of messages throughout each hour-long episode. The system's popularity sprang from its mix of serious and light-hearted comments.{{Citation needed|date=November 2012}} On average, around 3,500 texts are received during each hour-long programme, although 12,000 texts were once recorded in one frantic programme in 2004. Quantity of texts is generally related to the composition of the panel.{{Citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n===Twitter===\nOn 24 September 2009, the show launched its [[Twitter]] presence and the show's presenter has regularly announced its presence on Twitter since late 2009. Using the Twitter ID \"@bbcquestiontime\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/bbcquestiontime%7ctitle=Twitter%7cwork=twitter.com%7ctitle=Twitter%7cwork=twitter.com|title=Twitter|work=twitter.com}}</ref> it tweeted using the #bbcqt hashtag.  By early 2010, this had become one of the UK's most active \"Twitter backchannels\" to a TV show. @bbcquestiontime claimed 10,000 tweets had been sent around the show on 7 October 2010. The show had over 40,000 followers on Twitter by October 2010 and this exceeded 50,000 on the evening of 3 February 2011.\n\nOn 9 June 2011, ''Question Time'' became one of the most-tweeted about shows of the week in the UK, with 5,000 tweets during the programme, with tweeting continuing through to the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvgenius.net/socialtvstats/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=7 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125140921/http://www.tvgenius.net/socialtvstats/ |archivedate=25 November 2011 }}</ref> In addition to the more sober analysis of the discussion, ''Question Time'' also has a parallel Twitter backchannel based on the spoof account Dimblebot - purportedly a robot version of Dimbleby - where the entire premise of the programme is claimed to be a demonstration of Dimbleby's ability to defeat the panel. It became clear during the riot special that David Dimbleby knows of the existence of Dimblebot and the associated Dimbledance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2011/09/05/best-uk-twitter-accounts_n_949315.html|title=Ten Of The Best UK Twitter Feeds|work=The Huffington Post UK}}</ref><ref>[http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2011-08-12/dimblebot-helps-question-time-special-draw-35m-viewers Jack Seale, \"DIMBLEBOT helps Question Time special draw 3.5m viewers\",] ''Radio Times'',  12 August 2011.</ref> The @bbcquestiontime account now<ref>As of 3rd of June 2019.</ref> has over 500,000 followers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/bbcquestiontime|title=BBC Question Time (@bbcquestiontime) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|access-date=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, [[Sayeeda Warsi, Baroness Warsi]] and MP [[Debbie Abrahams]] sent an open letter to the programme's runners, after Question Time uploaded anti-immigrants Twitter comments from a far-right supporter who allegedly also ran for the [[National Front (UK)|National Front]] and showed support for the [[English Defence League]]. Baroness Warsi and Abrahams wrote in their letter: \u201cWe understand the producers of the show seek out \u2018controversial members of the audience \u2013 including those of far-right campaign groups \u2013 in an attempt to curry large ratings... By providing a platform for views that are racist or sexist, the institution is normalising them and contributing to the coarsening of public debate and the growing toxicity of our politics.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=Townsend|first=Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/mar/22/bbc-question-time-far-right-audience|title=BBC\u2019s Question Time accused of giving platform to far right|date=2020-03-22|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-03-22|last2=Thorpe|first2=Vanessa|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> \n\n== List of episodes ==\n{{See also|List of Question Time episodes}}\nAs of 2019, there have been over 1000 episodes broadcast.\n\n==Locations==\n{{multiple image\n|align     = right\n|direction = vertical\n|image1    = Scottish Parliament Debating Chamber 3.jpg\n|width1    = 250\n|image2    = WinchesterCathedral-west-wyrdlight.jpg\n|width2    = 250\n|image3    = Aston Webb Hall, Birmingham University.jpg\n|width3    = 250\n|caption3  = [[Scottish Parliament Building|The Scottish Parliament]], [[Winchester Cathedral]], and the [[University of Birmingham]]\n}}\n{{multiple image\n|align     = right\n|direction = vertical\n|image1    = Worcester Cathedral 20190211 132753 (47571669752).jpg\n|width1    = 250\n|image2    = Queens' Building (2899476115).jpg\n|width2    = 250\n|caption2  = [[Worcester Cathedral]] and [[Queen Mary University of London]]\n}}\nWhile chaired by Sir Robin Day, ''Question Time'' was predominantly filmed in [[London]]. It was during Peter Sissons tenure as presenter that ''Question Time'' started \"[[location shooting|moving around]] the country each week, taking the panel to audiences in different [[town]]s and [[city|cities]].\"<ref name=\"30 Years of Question Time\"/>\n\nOn occasion, ''Question Time'' has broadcast from outside the [[United Kingdom|UK]].  Locations have included: [[Brussels]], [[Johannesburg]], [[Miami]], [[Moscow]], [[New York City|New York]], [[Paris]], [[Shanghai]], [[Sydney]], and [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/8220219.stm|title=Question Time from Brussels in June 1984|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/question_time/your_comments/474096.stm|title=Question Time from Sydney in October 1999|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2002/09_september/10/qt_12sep.shtml|title=Question Time from New York in September 2002|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/3963147.stm|title=Question Time from Miami in October 2004|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/4335687.stm|title=Question Time from Shanghai in March 2005|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/4584401.stm|title=Question Time from Paris in May 2005|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/4074774.stm|title=Question Time from Johannesburg in July 2005|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/4856290.stm|title=Question Time from Moscow in March 2006|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00f81tc|title=Question Time from Washington in October 2008|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Dimbleby hosted the final edition of his 25-year tenure in the ''Question Time'' chair. For this edition, the programme returned \"to where it all started in 1979\": ''Question Time'' was broadcast from the Greenwood Theatre, now part of [[King's College London GKT School of Medical Education|King's College London Medical School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kcl.ac.uk/news/News-Article.aspx?id=eedafa08-45bb-47fe-acbd-9999be488ed3|title=David Dimbleby hosts last BBC Question Time at King's|website=King\u2019s College London}}</ref>\n\n===Venues===\n''Question Time'' has filmed in notable buildings, including: the [[Scottish Parliament Building|Scottish Parliament]], the [[Senedd building|Welsh Assembly]], and [[Palace of Westminster#Westminster Hall|Westminster Hall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0bnb623|title=Question Time from the Scottish Parliament|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0008sd4|title=Question Time from the Welsh Assembly}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/oct/20/bbc-broadcast-question-time-parliament|title=BBC to Broadcast Question Time From Parliament for First Time in 32 Years}}</ref>\n\nIt has also broadcast from: [[Heathrow Airport]], [[HM Prison Wormwood Scrubs|Wormwood Scrubs Prison]], and the cathedrals of [[Liverpool Cathedral|Liverpool]] and [[St Paul's Cathedral|St Paul's]], [[Winchester Cathedral|Winchester]] and [[Worcester Cathedral|Worcester]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-27445732|title=Question Time filmed from Heathrow Airport, Wormwood Scrubs, St Paul's Cathedral, and Winchester Cathedral|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2002/10_october/01/qt_liverpool.shtml|title=Question Time broadcasts from Liverpool Cathedral|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worcesternews.co.uk/news/10381291.bbc-question-time-live-from-worcester-cathedral|title=Question Time from Worcester Cathedral|website=Worcester News}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, ''Question Time'' has been held in prestigious universities, including: [[Queen Mary University of London]], and the universities of [[University of Birmingham|Birmingham]] and [[University of Nottingham|Nottingham]], [[University of Sheffield|Sheffield]] and [[University of York|York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qmhospitality.co.uk/about/news/2014news/items/qms-octagon-takes-time-out-for-questions.html|title=Question Time in London}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.birmingham.ac.uk/news/latest/2008/10/1Oct-Question.aspx|title=Question Time at University of Birmingham}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/news/nottingham-news/best-programme-ages-twitter-reacts-2798826|title=Twitter reacts to Question Time in Nottingham}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theneweuropean.co.uk/top-stories/who-is-on-the-bbc-question-time-panel-in-sheffield-tonight-march-28-2019-1-5964044|title=Who is on the BBC Question Time panel tonight?}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.york.ac.uk/news-and-events/features/question-time|title=Question Time at the University of York}}</ref>\n\nOther venues have included:\n{{div col|colwidth=17em}}\n* [[Aberystwyth University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aber.ac.uk/en/news/archive/2011/11/title-109568-en.html|title=Question Time from Aberystwyth University|website=Aberystwyth University}}</ref>\n* Nottingham's [[Albert Hall, Nottingham|Albert Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/15/michael-gove-on-question-times-eu-referendum-special-the-verdict|title=Michael Gove on Question Time's EU referendum special from Nottingham|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n* Basingstoke's [[The Anvil, Basingstoke|Anvil Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basingstokegazette.co.uk/news/10760324.topical-debate-as-question-time-visits-the-anvil/|title=Topical debate as Question Time visits The Anvil|website=Basingstoke Gazette}}</ref>\n* [[Aylesbury Waterside Theatre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buckinghamtoday.co.uk/news/bbc-s-question-time-comes-to-aylesbury-1-8796359|title=BBC's Question Time comes to Aylesbury|website=Buckingham and Winslow Advertiser}}</ref>\n* the [[Barbican Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/22974284d4674d1792c979b4da193591|title=Question Time from the Barbican Centre|website=BBC}}</ref>\n* Aberdeen's [[Beach Ballroom]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/news/local/bbcs-question-time-aired-aberdeen-tonight|title=BBC\u2019s Question Time to be aired from Aberdeen tonight|website=Evening Express}}</ref>\n* [[Bishop Auckland Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theneweuropean.co.uk/top-stories/who-is-on-the-bbc-question-time-panel-in-bishop-auckland-tonight-september-27-2018-1-5713703|title=Question Time from Bishop Auckland|website=The New European}}</ref>\n* [[Bishop's Stortford College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bishopsstortfordcollege.org/206/latest-news/post/719/question-time-airs-from-the-college|title=Question Time airs from the College|website=Bishop's Stortford College}}</ref>\n* Dundee's [[Caird Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/question-time-audience-against-snp-claim-independence-supporters-1-4062166|title=Question Time from Dundee|website=The Scotsman}}</ref>\n* the [[CBSO Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cbso.co.uk/inside-cbso-centre|title=Question Time from Birmingham|website=CBSO Centre}}</ref>\n* [[Chester Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chestertownhall.co.uk/stories/44/question-time-comes-to-chester-town-hall|title=Question Time comes to Chester Town Hall|website=Chester Town Hall}}</ref>\n* London's [[City Hall, London|City Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2013/qt-brand|title=Question Time from London\u2019s City Hall|website=BBC}}</ref>\n* Southend's [[Cliffs Pavilion]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chelmsfordweeklynews.co.uk/news/14881017._All_hail_purple_jumper_man____TV_viewers__glee_at_outspoken_audience_member_as_BBC_Question_Time_comes_to_Southend|title=BBC Question Time comes to Southend|website=Chelmsford Weekly News}}</ref>\n* [[Coventry University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/tv/bbc-question-time-panel-tonights-13190037|title=BBC Question Time from Coventry|website=Coventry Telegraph}}</ref>\n* Bexhill's [[De La Warr Pavilion]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/schools_question_time/8908991.stm|title=Question Time 2010|website=BBC}}</ref>\n* [[Dewsbury Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/news/tv/heres-your-chance-join-question-14927533|title=Dewsbury Town Hall hosts Question Time|website=Examiner Live}}</ref>\n* Glasgow's [[Easterhouse]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2013/question-time-st-pauls.html|title=Easterhouse hosts Question Time|website=BBC}}</ref>\n* [[Edinburgh Corn Exchange]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theedinburghreporter.co.uk/2013/06/heated-exchanges-on-question-time-from-edinburgh|title=Question Time from Edinburgh|website=The Edinburgh Reporter}}</ref>\n* [[Epsom College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.epsomcollege.org.uk/2019/05/epsom-college-to-host-bbc-question-time|title=Epsom College to host BBC Question Time|website=Epsom College}}</ref>\n* [[Glasgow Royal Concert Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://glasgowvenuehire.org.uk/pages/venue-details.aspx?vid=9|title=Question Time from Glasgow Royal Concert Hall|website=Glasgow Venue Hire}}</ref>\n* Wrexham's [[Wrexham Glynd\u0175r University|Glynd\u0175r University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/alan-johnson-bbc-question-time-2693748|title=Question Time from Wrexham|website=The Daily Post}}</ref>\n* [[Guildford High School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guildfordhigh.surrey.sch.uk/Hosting-Question-Time|title=Hosting Question Time|website=Guildford High School}}</ref>\n* [[James Allen's Girls' School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jags.org.uk/news/2018-11-27/Question-Time-comes-to-JAGS|title=Question Time comes to James Allen's Girls' School|website=James Allen's Girls' School}}</ref>\n* [[Kettering Conference Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.northantstelegraph.co.uk/news/panellists-confirmed-for-question-time-s-kettering-visit-1-8480287|title=Question Time\u2019s Kettering visit|website=Northamptonshire Telegraph}}</ref>\n* [[Kingswood Secondary Academy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingswoodsecondaryacademy.org/news/default.asp?storyID=258&pid=2&nid=2|title=BBC Question Time|website=Kingswood Secondary Academy}}</ref>\n* [[Leeds Beckett University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leedsbeckett.ac.uk/news/0318-leeds-beckett-hosts-lively-question-time|title=Leeds Beckett hosts Question Time|website=Leeds Beckett University}}</ref>\n* [[Leeds Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leeds-live.co.uk/news/celebs-tv/bbc-explains-controversial-decision-under-14407314|title=Question Time visits Leeds Town Hall|website=Leeds Live}}</ref>\n* the [[Lincoln Drill Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-17154444|title=Question Time from Lincoln Drill Hall|website=BBC}}</ref>\n* [[St Luke Old Street|LSO St Luke's]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BoOXac0nitS|title=Question Time at LSO St Luke's|website=Instagram}}</ref>\n* Birmingham's [[mac (Birmingham)|MAC]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://macbirmingham.co.uk/hire/room/theatre|title=Question Time in Birmingham|website=mac Birmingham}}</ref>\n* the [[Marshall Arena]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.miltonkeynes.co.uk/news/prime-minister-visits-milton-keynes-for-special-edition-of-question-time-at-arena-mk-1-7439217|title=Prime Minister visits Milton Keynes for special edition of Question Time at arena:mk|website=MK Citizen}}</ref>\n* [[Middlesbrough Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.middlesbrough.gov.uk/news/any-questions-middlesbrough-town-hall|title=Question Time from Middlesbrough Town Hall|website=Middlesbrough Council}}</ref>\n* [[MidKent College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/news/galloway-and-starkey-head-to-head-on-12422/|title=Question Time at MidKent College|website=Kent Online}}</ref>\n* [[Northampton High School, England|Northampton High School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://northamptonhigh.co.uk/2019/05/bbc-question-time-hosted-by-northampton-high-school|title=BBC Question Time hosted by Northampton High School|website=Northampton High School}}</ref>\n* [[North Oxfordshire Academy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banburyguardian.co.uk/whats-on/tv-and-film/bbc-question-time-coming-to-banbury-1-8579766|title=BBC Question Time coming to Banbury|website=Banbury Guardian}}</ref>\n* the [[Queen Elizabeth II Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/first-night-sure-footwork-from-dimbleby-question-time-bbc-television-1406768.html|title=Question Time from London|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n* [[Rochdale Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/magnificent-rochdale-town-hall-steals-6086868|title=\u2018Magnificent\u2019 Rochdale town hall steals show as BBC\u2019s Question Time comes to town|website=Manchester Evening News}}</ref>\n* the [[The Sage, Gateshead|Sage]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/bbc-question-time-recap-flagship-9438526|title=BBC Question Time from the Sage Gateshead|website=The Journal}}</ref>\n* Halifax's [[Square Chapel]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.squarechapel.co.uk/2019/06/question-time-comes-to-square-chapel-on-thursday-27-june|title=Question Time comes to Square Chapel|website=Square Chapel}}</ref>\n* [[Stamford School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stamfordmercury.co.uk/whats-on/bbc-question-time-to-be-filmed-at-stamford-school-1-7184910|title=BBC Question Time to be filmed at Stamford School|website=Rutland and Stamford Mercury}}</ref>\n* Norwich's [[St. Andrew's and Blackfriars' Hall, Norwich|St Andrew's Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edp24.co.uk/news/politics/panel-spar-over-tax-avoidance-at-bbc-question-time-from-norwich-1-3954645|title=BBC Question Time from Norwich|website=Eastern Daily Press}}</ref>\n* Newbury's [[St Bartholomew's School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newburytoday.co.uk/news/news/12451/bbc-s-question-time-comes-to-newbury-tonight-thurs.html|title=BBC's Question Time comes to Newbury|website=Newbury Today}}</ref>\n* [[St Dunstan's College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stdunstans.org.uk/media/news/article/2003/Question-Time-is-coming-to-St-Dunstan-s-College|title=Question Time is coming to St Dunstan's College|website=St Dunstan's College}}</ref>\n* Milford Haven's [[Torch Theatre, Milford Haven|Torch Theatre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milfordmercury.co.uk/news/17005310.bbc-political-debate-programme-question-time-to-come-to-torch-theatre|title=Question Time to come to Torch Theatre|website=Milford Mercury}}</ref>\n* the [[University of Brighton]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brighton.ac.uk/about-us/news-and-events/news/2014/03-28_university-hosts-question-time.aspx|title=Brighton hosts Question Time|website=University of Brighton}}</ref>\n* the [[University of Chichester]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chichester.co.uk/news/politics/bbcqt-question-time-coming-to-chichester-1-8984968|title=Question Time coming to Chichester|website=Chichester Observer}}</ref>\n* the [[University of Plymouth]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.plymouth.ac.uk/news/question-time-is-broadcast-from-the-house|title=Question Time from University of Plymouth|website=University of Plymouth}}</ref>\n* the [[University of West London]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwl.ac.uk/news-events/news/uwl-hosts-bbc\u2019s-question-time-0|title=UWL hosts BBC\u2019s Question Time|website=University of West London}}</ref>\n* Stirling's [[Wallace High School, Stirling|Wallace High School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/wallacehighsch/status/799259968138518528|title=Question Time from Stirling|website=Twitter}}</ref>\n* [[Walsall Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/politics/2016/05/19/lib-dem-leader-on-panel-for-question-time-in-walsall|title=Question Time in Walsall|website=Express and Star}}</ref>\n* [[Weymouth College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/10157942.question-time-comes-to-weymouth|title=Question Time comes to Weymouth|website=Dorset Echo}}</ref>\n* Gravesend's [[Woodville Halls Theatre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/gravesend/news/question-time-comes-to-gravesend-a84748|title=Question Time comes to Gravesend|website=Kent Online}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Production===\nThe show is recorded at [[location shooting|different venues]] throughout the UK. Although, as part of plans to relocate BBC production around the UK, the main office of the programme will move to [[BBC Scotland]] in [[Glasgow]], the itinerant nature of the programme will continue.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/mar/24/newsnight-review-revamp BBC2's \"Newsnight Review to get revamp\",] ''The Guardian'', 24 March 2009.</ref>\n\n==Famous editions==\nIn early 1981, [[David Steel]] declared his support in principle for \"a marriage\" between the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] and any party which might be formed by the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)#Creation of the SDP|Gang of Four]]; [[David Owen]], who was also on the programme, said he could see advantages in an \"electoral alliance\" between them. This prefigured the period 1983\u20131987 when Owen and Steel were Leaders of the [[SDP-Liberal Alliance]] and tension grew over whether their deal was a prelude to a merger of the parties or merely a temporary electoral pact.\n\nDuring the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 election campaign]], [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[Francis Pym]] was asked by an A-level student named Andy Davis about the implications of the Conservatives winning the election with a landslide victory. He began by casting doubt on the likelihood of this happening and then observed \"I think landslides on the whole don't produce successful governments\". Margaret Thatcher later wrote that the remark \"struck a wrong note\": \"people drew the inference that he did not want us to win a large majority\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Thatcher |first=Margaret |title=The Downing Street Years |url=https://archive.org/details/downingstreetyea00that |url-access=registration |publisher=HarperCollins |year=1993 |page=[https://archive.org/details/downingstreetyea00that/page/n329 294] |ISBN=0002550490}}</ref> After the election (won by the Conservatives on a landslide) she sacked him as [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]], partly because of his [[gaffe]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Thatcher |first=Margaret |title=The Downing Street Years |url=https://archive.org/details/downingstreetyea00that |url-access=registration |publisher=HarperCollins |year=1993 |page=[https://archive.org/details/downingstreetyea00that/page/n341 306] |ISBN=0002550490}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1984 edition, [[Alan Clark]], a junior government Minister at the time, was openly critical of a government decision to buy a foreign-made missile system, prompting guest host [[Sue Lawley]] to ask the audience, \"Is there anyone here who wishes to defend the government on this, because its Minister doesn't?\"\n\nA 1994 edition was notable for a confrontation between [[Jeffrey Archer]] and the historian [[David Starkey]] over the age of homosexual consent. After arguing that 18 should be the age of consent, Archer was attacked by Starkey who told him: \"Englishmen like you enjoy sitting on the fence so much because you enjoy the sensation.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = Havard | first = Ed | title = Question Time defined by 'epic' battles | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/9366830.stm | publisher = news.bbc.co.uk | date = 20 January 2011 | accessdate = 16 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe programme broadcast on 13 September 2001, which was devoted to the political implications of the [[11 September 2001 attacks]], featured many contributions from members of the audience who were anti-American, expressing the view that \"the United States had it coming\". The BBC received more than 2,000 complaints and later apologised to viewers for causing offence, stating that the edition should not have been broadcast live, but rather should have been recorded and edited.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/1544897.stm BBC chief apologises for terror debate], BBC News, 15 September 2001</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the editor of ''[[Private Eye]]'', [[Ian Hislop]], made an open attack on Jeffrey Archer, who had been imprisoned for [[perjury]], when his wife [[Mary Archer]] was a fellow panellist. She was noticeably angry that the issue had been raised and criticised Hislop after the recording had finished.\n\nIn March 2007, an Iraq Special was broadcast, featuring [[Tony Benn]], [[Benazir Bhutto]], [[Des Browne]], [[Liam Fox]], [[Charles Kennedy]] and, via [[video link]] from [[Washington D.C.]], [[John R. Bolton]]. The episode is particularly memorable for the clashes between Benn and Bolton.\n\nOn 11 October 2007, former editor of ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper [[Kelvin MacKenzie]] appeared on the programme in [[Cheltenham]] and launched an attack on Scotland. During a debate about tax, MacKenzie claimed that \"Scotland believes not in entrepreneurialism like London and the south east... Scots enjoy spending it (money) but they don't enjoy creating it, which is the opposite to down south.\" The comments came as part of an attack on [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] who MacKenzie said could not be trusted to manage the British economy because he was \"a Scot\" and a \"socialist\", and insisting that this was relevant to the debate. Fellow panellist [[Chuka Umunna]] from the [[think tank]] Compass called his comments \"absolutely disgraceful\", and booing and jeering were heard from the Cheltenham studio audience. The BBC received 350 complaints and MacKenzie's comments drew widespread criticism in both Scotland and England. On 3 July 2008, it was reported that the BBC Trust's editorial complaints unit had cleared the programme of any wrongdoing. ''Question Time'' then proceeded to broadcast the following question from Nick Hartley as part of the programme on the same evening: \"After the media coverage of [Andy] Murray's rise and fall, are we now to infer that the English resent the Scots more than the Scots resent the English?\" MacKenzie reappeared on the programme in [[Cardiff]] on 17 May 2012.\n\nAfter he was elected to the European Parliament, [[Nick Griffin]] the leader of the [[British National Party]] was invited onto ''Question Time'' for the first time, to appear on 22 October 2009. The decision led to [[Question Time British National Party controversy|controversy and political debate]]. Hundreds of people protested outside [[BBC Television Centre]] as the edition was filmed; six people were arrested after 25 protesters forced their way into the main reception.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2009/oct/22/bnp-question-time-live-buildup \"BNP on Question Time\",] ''The Guardian'', 22 October 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8321157.stm | work=BBC News | title=Angry scenes face Griffin at BBC | date=22 October 2009 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> The edition attracted eight million viewers,<ref name=BNPcontroversy>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8322322.stm|title= Griffin complaint over BBC 'mob'|publisher=BBC News|date= 23 October 2009|accessdate= 23 October 2009}}</ref> and also drew a large number of complaints as a result of its content. Griffin himself said that he would make a formal complaint to the BBC for the way he believed he was treated by the show's other guests and the audience, who he described as a \"lynch mob.\"<ref name=BNPcontroversy/>\n\nAn edition aired on 19 May 2011 was recorded at [[Wormwood Scrubs (HM Prison)|Wormwood Scrubs Prison]] in [[London]]. The episode was the first to feature prisoners as part of the audience, while panellists included [[Secretary of State for Justice|Justice Secretary]] [[Kenneth Clarke|Ken Clarke]] who attempted to defend controversial remarks he had made earlier in the week about rape sentencing.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/may/20/question-time-tv-ratings|title= Ken Clarke detains 3 million on Question Time|publisher= Guardian Media Group|work= The Guardian|first= Ben|last= Dowell|date= 20 May 2011|accessdate= 21 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nA special edition of the programme was aired on 11 August 2011 following the [[2011 England riots|outbreak of rioting]] which had occurred during the previous weekend and earlier that week.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/aug/12/question-time-riots-special|title= Question Time riots special draws 3.6m viewers|publisher= Guardian Media Group|work= The Guardian|first= Ben|last= Dowell|date= 12 August 2011|accessdate= 16 August 2011}}</ref> ''Question Time'' had been off air for its annual summer break at the time and the edition was a scheduled at short notice due to the English riots.\n\nAn [[Question Time George Galloway in Finchley controversy|appearance by George Galloway]] on the edition of 5 February 2015 recorded in Finchley gained much negative comment before the broadcast. Inviting Galloway, a politician who has been outspoken about Israel, onto the programme was thought to be provocative and insensitive because Finchley has a large Jewish minority.<ref name=\"Rashty\">Sandy Rashty [http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/129151/galloway-question-time-appearance-chance-call-mp-account-says-board \"Galloway Question Time appearance is chance to call MP to account, says Board\"], ''The Jewish Chronicle'', 29 January 2015</ref> Galloway, who was heckled during a discussion about antisemitism, thought he had been defamed by a question posed to him, which insinuated that he should share some of the blame for a rise in antisemitic incidents during 2014.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/feb/06/george-galloway-accuses-bbc-over-question-time-set-up \"George Galloway accuses BBC over Question Time 'set-up'\"], ''The Guardian'', 6 February 2015</ref>\n\nOn 23 November 2017, the programme was shortened because an audience member became ill and could not be safely moved.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42104904|title=Question Time cut short as woman falls ill|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 19th March 2020, the programme was broadcast for the first time without an audience in Weston-super-mare due to the Coronavirus outbreak. \n\nOn 26th March 2020, the programme moved to a semi-permanent home at the IMG Studios at Stockley Park in London as a measure to prevent unnecessary travel during the Coronavirus outbreak, the show followed a different format with no audience and the panellists sitting 2m apart to follow the social distancing regulations.\n\n==Audience figures==\nAudience figures for ''Question Time'' are usually around 2.7 million.{{Citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\nThe highest audience figures to date were recorded when Nick Griffin of the BNP appeared in an [[Question Time British National Party controversy|episode]] on 22 October 2009; the audience reaching 8.3&nbsp;million viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atvtoday.co.uk/8-million-watch-bnp-on-question-time/|title=8 Million Watch BNP on Question Time|website=ATV Today}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 May 2009, ''Question Time'' discussed the [[Disclosure of expenses of British Members of Parliament|MPs' expenses row]], with audience members heckling guest panellists [[Menzies Campbell]] and [[Margaret Beckett]], the Labour MP, who was booed by the audience for insisting that her expenses were her privilege. The TV audience reached 3.8&nbsp;million.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\n3.4&nbsp;million people watched in 2003 at the start of the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|war on Iraq]].\n\n==Similar programmes==\n* In 1994, [[BBC Scotland]] launched their own local debate show called ''Words with Wark'' which was broadcast on [[BBC One Scotland]] usually on the first Thursday of every month and this was presented by [[Kirsty Wark]]. The programme was axed in 1998.\n* Until 2010, [[BBC One Northern Ireland]] replaced ''Question Time'' with the more local debate show ''Let's Talk'' at least once a month hosted by Mark Carruthers, but this show has been axed and brought under the Spotlight brand. It is now shown once a month on Tuesday night with Noel Thompson. BBC One NI have their own political show called ''The View'': this is broadcast live from 10.35pm to 11.05pm, presented by Mark Carruthers, and is followed by ''Question Time''. If Question Time is made in Northern Ireland.\n* [[BBC World]] produces an Indian version of the programme for such viewers.\n* The Irish broadcaster [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]] produced a similar show, ''[[Questions and Answers (TV series)|Questions and Answers]]'', which ran from 1986 to 2009, and was replaced by ''[[The Frontline (Irish TV series)|The Frontline]]'', which is of a similar format.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/0814/1224252553041.html|title=Recession leaves its mark on RT\u00c9 schedule|date=14 August 2009|work=[[Irish Times]]|accessdate=12 September 2009}}</ref>\n* In March 2010, [[Dermot O'Leary]] hosted a spinoff edition of the show, which was broadcast on [[BBC Three]]. It was called ''First Time Voters' Question Time'', and the show was aimed at first time voters. This version of the programme was later commissioned on a permanent, monthly basis on BBC Three, to now be hosted by [[Richard Bacon (TV presenter)|Richard Bacon]], and re-titled ''Young Voters' Question Time''. He was replaced by [[Jake Humphrey]] then by [[Rick Edwards]] with [[Tina Daheley]], and the show was renamed ''Free Speech'' which goes out every month.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/09_september/21/question.shtml Young Voters' Question Time becomes permanent fixture on BBC Three] BBC Press Office, 21 September 2010</ref>\n*In 2007, the BBC commissioned ''[[The Big Questions]]'', a new programme with a similar format to ''Question Time'', which focuses on ethical and religious issues. It is broadcast on BBC One on Sunday mornings between 10{{nbsp}}am and 11{{nbsp}}am. Both programmes are produced by Mentorn Media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mentorn.tv/|title=MentornMedia|website=Mentorn Media}}</ref>\n* In 2008, the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] launched a similar, Australian version of the programme, called ''[[Q&A (Australian talk show)|Q&A]]''. Airing live weekly, it has become a critical success, achieving extremely positive ratings for the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] in Australia, with a wide audience from a range of demographics not all of which are normally noted for their interest in the Australian political scene.\n* In 2011, [[Azerbaijan]] launched its own version of the programme. ''[[Open Talk]]'' {{lang-az|A\u00e7\u0131q s\u00f6hb\u0259t}} is a weekly debate [[ANS TV]] television programme in Azerbaijan, based on ''Question Time''. The show features political leaders as well as other public figures. ''Open Talk'' is presented by [[Sevinj Osmanqizi]].\n\n===Schools edition===\nSeveral schools editions have been broadcast:\nOn 20 June 2005, with a panel of [[Tony Benn]], [[Justine Greening]], [[Lembit Opik]], [[June Sarpong]] and [[Otis Ferry]].<ref name=\"Classic Question Times\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/4549698.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Programmes - Question Time - Classic Question Times|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> On 6 July 2006, with a twenty-year-old student joining [[David Miliband]], [[Richard and Judy|Richard Madelely]], [[Sebastian Coe|Lord Coe]] and [[Julia Goldsworthy]].<ref name=\"Classic Question Times\"/>\nOn 5 July 2007, an 18-year-old student joined a panel of [[Ed Miliband]], [[Sayeeda Warsi]], [[Davina McCall]] and [[Douglas Murray (author)|Douglas Murray]].<ref name=\"Classic Question Times\"/> On 9 July 2009, one of the panellists was an eighteen-year-old student. Other panellists were [[Andy Burnham]], [[Jeremy Hunt (politician)|Jeremy Hunt]], [[Sarah Teather]] and [[Shami Chakrabarti]].<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00lp1wj ''Question Time, Schools Edition''], BBC One, 9 July 2009.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n===Other sources===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Bailey, Ric (26 January 2005) [http://news.bbc.co.uk/newswatch/ukfs/hi/newsid_4200000/newsid_4202800/4202877.stm \"NewsWatch: Question Time for Question Time\"] ''BBC News'' Retrieved 9 July 2005.\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/3869985.stm \"The Best of ''Question Time''\"]  ''BBC News'' Retrieved 9 July 2005.\n* Guyon, Janet (29 November 2001) [https://web.archive.org/web/20050206094842/http://www.mutualofamerica.com/articles/Fortune/2001_11_29/American.asp \"Fortune: The New Future\u2014The American Way\"] ''Mutual of America'' Retrieved 9 July 2005.\n* Shawcross, William (17 September 2001) [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2001/sep/17/september11.usa30 \"Stop This Racism\"] ''The Guardian'' Retrieved 9 July 2005.\n{{div col end}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0081t8r ''Question Time Extra'']\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01sfcms ''Question Time Extra Time'']\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episodes/b006t1q9/question-time BBC iPlayer]\n* [https://twitter.com/bbcquestiontime Twitter]\n* [https://instagram.com/bbcquestiontime Instagram]\n* [https://youtube.com/watch?v=3SUklxFF4pY ''Question Time'' set-up and breakdown time lapse]\n* {{IMDb title|0267212|Question Time}}\n\n{{Portal|BBC}}\n{{BBC News}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Question Time (TV Series)}}\n[[Category:1979 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1970s British political television series]]\n[[Category:1980s British political television series]]\n[[Category:1990s British political television series]]\n[[Category:2000s British political television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British political television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British political television series]]\n[[Category:BBC News]]\n[[Category:BBC television news programmes]]\n[[Category:BBC Television programmes]]\n[[Category:Debate television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Tinopolis]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Question Time\n| image                    = BBC Question Time.png\n| caption                  = \n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = [[News#Newsworthiness|Topical]] [[debate]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006t1q9|title=Question Time genre}}</ref>\n| creator                  = \n| director                 = Rob Hopkin<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0by97hj|title=Rob Hopkin: Question Time Director}}</ref>\n| developer                = \n| presenter                = {{Nowrap|'''Current:'''<br>[[Fiona Bruce]] (2019\u2013)<br>'''Former:'''<br>[[Robin Day|Sir Robin Day]] (1979\u20131989)<br>[[Peter Sissons]] (1989\u20131993)<br>[[David Dimbleby]] (1994\u20132018)}}\n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = \n| country                  = [[United Kingdom]]\n| language                 = [[English language|English]]\n| executive_producer       = [[Nicolai Gentchev]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0by97hj|title=Nicolai Gentchev: Question Time Executive Producer}}</ref>\n| producer                 = \n| editor                   = Hilary O'Neill<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0by97hj|title=Hilary O'Neill: Question Time Editor}}</ref>\n| location                 = [[location shooting|On location]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5vyK2GwYrdQGFvCJyKNfZhn/join-the-question-time-audience/contact|title=Question Time filming locations}}</ref><br>[[Question Time (TV programme)#Locations|(list of locations)]]\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 60 minutes\n| company                  = [[Brian Lapping Productions]] (previously)<br>[[Tinopolis|Mentorn Media]] (currently)\n| channel                  = [[BBC One]]\n| picture_format           = [[576i]] ([[16:9]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])<br>[[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format.            = \n| first_run                = \n| first_aired              = {{Start date|1979|9|25|df=yes}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| num_episodes             = 1,429<br>(as of 13 December 2019)\n| list_episodes            = List of Question Time episodes\n| related                  = ''[[Any Answers?]]''<br>''[[Any Questions?]]''<br>''[[The Big Questions]]''<br>''[[Dateline London]]''<br>''[[HARDtalk]]''<br>''[[Newsnight]]''<br>''Question Time Extra Time''\n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/questiontime\n| website_title            = ''Question Time''\n| production_website       = http://www.mentorn.tv/programmes/programme-list/question-time\n| production_website_title = ''Mentorn Media''\n}}\n\n'''''Question Time''''' is a [[News#Newsworthiness|topical]] [[debate]] programme, typically broadcast on [[BBC One]] at 10:35 pm on Thursdays.  It is usually repeated on [[BBC Two]] and on [[BBC Parliament]], later in the week.  ''Question Time'' is also available on [[BBC iPlayer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0003227|title=Question Time broadcast times|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episodes/b006t1q9|title=Question Time available on BBC iPlayer|website=BBC}}</ref> [[Fiona Bruce]] currently [[Chairperson|chairs]] the show having succeeded [[David Dimbleby]] as presenter in January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0by97hj|title=Fiona Bruce presents her first Question Time|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n[[Tinopolis|Mentorn]] has [[production company|produced]] the programme since 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2007/03_march/08/question.shtml|title=Press Office - Mentorn wins back Question Time contract|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Origins==\n''Question Time'' was first broadcast on Tuesday 25 September 1979, based on the [[BBC Radio 4]] programme ''[[Any Questions?]]''. The first panel consisted of [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of parliament|MP]] [[Michael Foot]], author [[Edna O'Brien]], [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician [[Teddy Taylor]], and the [[Archbishop of Liverpool]] [[Derek Worlock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/8220219.stm|title=In pictures: 30 years of Question Time|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\n''Question Time'' panels are typically composed of five public figures, \"nearly always [including] a representative from the [[Government of the United Kingdom|UK government]] and the [[Official Opposition Shadow Cabinet (United Kingdom)|official opposition]].\" The panel also features \"representatives from other [[political party|political parties]] across the series, taking as [the] guide the level of electoral support at national level which each party enjoys.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5HrMm77Yz7vwzCZZ570nTdp/frequently-asked-questions|title=Composition of Question Time panels|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nHigh-profile [[journalist]]s and [[author]]s, [[television presenter|television]] and [[radio personality|radio broadcasters]], and [[comedian]]s, join the panel, as do [[senior management|business leaders]] from well-known companies, and [[credential|leading]] or [[expert]] [[academic personnel|academics]], [[lawyer]]s, [[police officer]]s, and [[clergy|clerics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006t1q9/episodes/guide|title=Question Time panels|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n[[Audience]] members are selected by the 'audience producer' (Alison Fuller<ref>https://www.thecanary.co/uk/news/2019/05/20/snp-deputy-blasts-bbc-question-time-for-audience-stuffed-full-of-tory-plants/</ref>) based on age, [[gender]], [[job|occupation]], [[ethnic group|ethnicity]], [[disability|disability status]], voting intention, voting history, and party membership.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/send/u21723349?ptrt=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006t1q9|title=Question Time audience selection process|website=BBC}}</ref> The audience members are \"requested to come up with two questions, to be considered for the programme.\" The panel hears the questions for the first time, when the audience members ask them. Applicants are contacted on the Monday, Tuesday, or Wednesday before the programme.  Although, due to a \"[[popularity|high volume of requests]],\" the team are unable to call everyone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/send/u21723349?ptrt=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006t1q9|title=Question Time audience|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n''Question Time'' is usually recorded \"as-live\", and in a [[Take#Single-takes|single-take]], shortly before transmission. The programme is only edited on \"very rare\" occasions for [[law|legal]] or [[taste (sociology)|taste]] reasons, or because it over-runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/5HrMm77Yz7vwzCZZ570nTdp/frequently-asked-questions|title=Question Time recordings|website=BBC}}</ref> For example, ''[[The Observer]]'' newspaper reported in 1986 that \"The BBC's lawyers ordered nine seconds of ''Question Time'' to be deleted by the old-fashioned method of simply cutting off the sound\".<ref>'\"High Tech, low tech, no tech\"'', The Observer,'' 9 February 1986</ref>\n\n==Presenters==\n===Sir Robin Day===\nVeteran broadcaster [[Robin Day|Sir Robin Day]] was the programme's first [[chairman|chair]], presenting it for nearly 10 years until June 1989. ''Question Time'' soon gained [[popularity]] under Day's lead, with his quick [[wit]] and [[interrogation]] skills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/talking_point/870169.stm|title=Your tributes to Sir Robin Day|website=BBC}}</ref> His famous [[catchphrase]] when he had introduced the panel was: \"There they are, and here we go.\"<ref name=\"30 Years of Question Time\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/8220219.stm|title=30 Years of Question Time|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nThe programme was mainly filmed at the Greenwood Theatre in London on the south side of [[London Bridge]]. Day's last appearance as presenter was broadcast from [[Paris]] on 12 July 1989. He was allowed to choose his own guests.<ref name=\"Sissons 2012\"/>\n\n===Peter Sissons===\n{{multiple image\n|align     = right\n|direction = vertical\n|image1    = Barbican Silk Street - geograph.org.uk - 978.jpg\n|width1    = 250\n|caption1  = [[Barbican Centre|The Barbican Centre]]\n}}\nAfter [[Robin Day|Day]] retired, [[Peter Sissons]] took over and continued until 1993. The [[BBC]] decided to widen the programme's appeal by [[location shooting|moving it around the country]]. The programme also changed its London location from the Greenwood Theatre to the [[Barbican Centre]]. Sissons' tenure as ''Question Time'' chair included three different editors. There were several problems during filming, including a [[bomb threat|bomb scare]] during a live recording, which resulted in the programme being taken off the air, and the [[death]] of an audience member who [[collapse (medical)|collapsed]] while recording.<ref name=\"Sissons 2012\">{{cite book|last=Sissons|first=Peter|title=When One Door Closes|year=2012|publisher=Biteback|isbn=978-1-84954-075-9}}</ref>\n\nThe programme continued to enjoy good ratings during this period, notably on the day of [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s resignation on 22 November 1990, which featured two different panels over two editions.<ref name=\"Sissons 2012\"/>\n\nOn 1 October 2019, Sissons' agent announced the former BBC and ITN newsreader and ''Question Time'' host died peacefully at the age of 77, with tributes paid by fellow journalists, and director-general [[Tony Hall, Baron Hall of Birkenhead|Tony Hall]].\n\n===David Dimbleby===\n[[David Dimbleby]] succeeded Sissons as ''Question Time'' presenter in 1994, after the BBC held two pilot show [[audition]]s between Dimbleby and [[Jeremy Paxman]], with two different [[audience]]s and two different panels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/dimbleby-provides-answer-for-question-time-1466997.html |title=Dimbleby provides answer for 'Question Time'|work=The Independent |date=12 December 1993 |accessdate=7 September 2014 }}</ref> For a brief period under Dimbleby in the mid-1990s, there were a number of variations to the format, including the audience using voting keypads to take a poll of the audience at the end of the programme and Dimbleby getting out of his seat at intervals to question the audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/first-night-sure-footwork-from-dimbleby-question-time-bbc-television-1406768.html |title=First Night: Sure footwork from Dimbleby: 'Question Time', BBC Television |work=The Independent |date=14 January 1994 |accessdate=7 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nDimbleby presented ''Question Time'' for 25 years, the programme's longest-serving presenter, until his final programme, aged 80, on 13 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/tv-radio/david-dimbleby-question-time-last-episode-tonight-bbc-fiona-bruce-brexit-theresa-may-vote-a8681316.html |title=David Dimbleby to host his final ever episode of Question Time tonight |newspaper=The Independent |date=13 December 2018  |author=Anu Shukla}}</ref>\n\n===Fiona Bruce===\nIn December 2018, the BBC announced that [[Fiona Bruce]] would succeed Dimbleby as [[discussion moderator|moderator]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2018/fiona-bruce-question-time|title=Fiona Bruce announced as new Question Time presenter |date=7 December 2018 |access-date=7 December 2018|website=BBC}}</ref> Bruce\u2014along with [[Samira Ahmed]], [[Victoria Derbyshire]], [[Emily Maitlis]], [[Nick Robinson (journalist)|Nick Robinson]], and [[Kirsty Wark]]\u2014attended October 2018 [[audition]]s at London's [[James Allen's Girls' School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/oct/08/emily-maitlis-and-nick-robinson-audition-in-question-time-pilots|title=Ahmed, Maitlis, Robinson, and Wark audition for Question Time role|website=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/oct/09/victoria-derbyshire-and-fiona-bruce-filmed-for-question-time-job-bbc-auditions-david-dimbleby|title=Bruce and Derbyshire audition for Question Time role|website=The Guardian}}</ref> She presented her first ''Question Time'' in January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-politics-46833072/question-time-fiona-bruce-s-debut-proves-popular|title=Praise for Fiona Bruce's first Question Time|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=11 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Guest presenters===\n''Question Time'' has seen various presenters deputise for the main chair. [[Ludovic Kennedy|Sir Ludovic Kennedy]], [[Sue Lawley]], [[Bernard Levin]], and [[Donald MacCormick]], all [[discussion moderator|moderated]] in Day's place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?adv=0&q=Question+Time+with+Ludovic+Kennedy&media=all&yf=1923&yt=2009&mf=1&mt=12&tf=00%3A00&tt=00%3A00#search|title=Sir Ludovic Kennedy presents in place of Day|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?adv=0&q=Question+Time+with+Sue+Lawley&media=all&yf=1923&yt=2009&mf=1&mt=12&tf=00%3A00&tt=00%3A00#search|title=Sue Lawley holds Day's fort|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?adv=0&q=Question+Time+with+Bernard+Levin&media=all&yf=1923&yt=2009&mf=1&mt=12&tf=00%3A00&tt=00%3A00#search|title=Bernard Levin deputises for Day|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/search/0/20?adv=0&q=Question+Time+with+Donald+MacCormick&media=all&yf=1923&yt=2009&mf=1&mt=12&tf=00%3A00&tt=00%3A00#search|title=Donald MacCormick in lieu of Day|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, [[John Humphrys]] presented in lieu of Dimbleby, who had been \"injured by a bullock at his farm\" causing him \"briefly to be knocked out.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8356943.stm|title=John Humphrys presents in lieu of Dimbleby|website=BBC}}</ref> In June 2017, [[Nick Robinson (journalist)|Nick Robinson]] presented a \"Leaders Special\" edition of ''Question Time''.  The programme was moved for news coverage of the [[2017 London Bridge attack|London Bridge attack]].  Dimbleby was preparing for the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|General Election coverage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08tj1sg|title=Nick Robinson presents Question Time Leaders Special|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Editors==\nCharlie Courtauld was editor from 1998 to 2000, leaving to join the ''[[Independent on Sunday]]'' as its comment editor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.linkedin.com/pub/charlie-courtauld/11/b9/940|title =LinkedIn|website=LinkedIn}}</ref><ref name=Collins>{{cite news |first=Nick |last=Collins |title=Question Time's previous editors |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/8375253/Question-Times-previous-editors.html |location = London |work=Daily Telegraph |date=11 March 2011 }}</ref> [[Nick Pisani]] was appointed in 2000, resigning abruptly in May 2005 after news was leaked that he had been offered a job as David Cameron's head of TV presentation.<ref name=Collins />Ed Havard was made acting editor in May 2005 after Pisani left. During his time in charge the BBC offered a seat on the panel to Nick Griffin in 2009. He left when the programme's production base moved to Glasgow.<ref name=Collins />\n\nGill Penlington, the ITV News political producer, was made interim editor in May 2008, when the BBC gave Ed Havard a year-long sabbatical.<ref name=Collins />\n\n==Interactivity==\n\n===SMS contributions===\nViewers of the show can submit comments to the show via [[Short Message Service|SMS]]; until October 2012 a selection of those comments was posted on [[Ceefax]]. Comments were edited and put to air by a team of four journalists based at Television Centre in London. The system displayed one message at a time, and usually showed several tens of messages throughout each hour-long episode. The system's popularity sprang from its mix of serious and light-hearted comments.{{Citation needed|date=November 2012}} On average, around 3,500 texts are received during each hour-long programme, although 12,000 texts were once recorded in one frantic programme in 2004. Quantity of texts is generally related to the composition of the panel.{{Citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n===Twitter===\nOn 24 September 2009, the show launched its [[Twitter]] presence and the show's presenter has regularly announced its presence on Twitter since late 2009. Using the Twitter ID \"@bbcquestiontime\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/bbcquestiontime%7ctitle=Twitter%7cwork=twitter.com%7ctitle=Twitter%7cwork=twitter.com|title=Twitter|work=twitter.com}}</ref> it tweeted using the #bbcqt hashtag.  By early 2010, this had become one of the UK's most active \"Twitter backchannels\" to a TV show. @bbcquestiontime claimed 10,000 tweets had been sent around the show on 7 October 2010. The show had over 40,000 followers on Twitter by October 2010 and this exceeded 50,000 on the evening of 3 February 2011.\n\nOn 9 June 2011, ''Question Time'' became one of the most-tweeted about shows of the week in the UK, with 5,000 tweets during the programme, with tweeting continuing through to the next day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvgenius.net/socialtvstats/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=7 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125140921/http://www.tvgenius.net/socialtvstats/ |archivedate=25 November 2011 }}</ref> In addition to the more sober analysis of the discussion, ''Question Time'' also has a parallel Twitter backchannel based on the spoof account Dimblebot - purportedly a robot version of Dimbleby - where the entire premise of the programme is claimed to be a demonstration of Dimbleby's ability to defeat the panel. It became clear during the riot special that David Dimbleby knows of the existence of Dimblebot and the associated Dimbledance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2011/09/05/best-uk-twitter-accounts_n_949315.html|title=Ten Of The Best UK Twitter Feeds|work=The Huffington Post UK}}</ref><ref>[http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2011-08-12/dimblebot-helps-question-time-special-draw-35m-viewers Jack Seale, \"DIMBLEBOT helps Question Time special draw 3.5m viewers\",] ''Radio Times'',  12 August 2011.</ref> The @bbcquestiontime account now<ref>As of 3rd of June 2019.</ref> has over 500,000 followers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/bbcquestiontime|title=BBC Question Time (@bbcquestiontime) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|access-date=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, [[Sayeeda Warsi, Baroness Warsi]] and MP [[Debbie Abrahams]] sent an open letter to the programme's runners, after Question Time uploaded anti-immigrants Twitter comments from a far-right supporter who allegedly also ran for the [[National Front (UK)|National Front]] and showed support for the [[English Defence League]]. Baroness Warsi and Abrahams wrote in their letter: \u201cWe understand the producers of the show seek out \u2018controversial members of the audience \u2013 including those of far-right campaign groups \u2013 in an attempt to curry large ratings... By providing a platform for views that are racist or sexist, the institution is normalising them and contributing to the coarsening of public debate and the growing toxicity of our politics.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=Townsend|first=Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/mar/22/bbc-question-time-far-right-audience|title=BBC\u2019s Question Time accused of giving platform to far right|date=2020-03-22|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-03-22|last2=Thorpe|first2=Vanessa|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> \n\n== List of episodes ==\n{{See also|List of Question Time episodes}}\nAs of 2019, there have been over 1000 episodes broadcast.\n\n==Locations==\n{{multiple image\n|align     = right\n|direction = vertical\n|image1    = Scottish Parliament Debating Chamber 3.jpg\n|width1    = 250\n|image2    = WinchesterCathedral-west-wyrdlight.jpg\n|width2    = 250\n|image3    = Aston Webb Hall, Birmingham University.jpg\n|width3    = 250\n|caption3  = [[Scottish Parliament Building|The Scottish Parliament]], [[Winchester Cathedral]], and the [[University of Birmingham]]\n}}\n{{multiple image\n|align     = right\n|direction = vertical\n|image1    = Worcester Cathedral 20190211 132753 (47571669752).jpg\n|width1    = 250\n|image2    = Queens' Building (2899476115).jpg\n|width2    = 250\n|caption2  = [[Worcester Cathedral]] and [[Queen Mary University of London]]\n}}\nWhile chaired by Sir Robin Day, ''Question Time'' was predominantly filmed in [[London]]. It was during Peter Sissons tenure as presenter that ''Question Time'' started \"[[location shooting|moving around]] the country each week, taking the panel to audiences in different [[town]]s and [[city|cities]].\"<ref name=\"30 Years of Question Time\"/>\n\nOn occasion, ''Question Time'' has broadcast from outside the [[United Kingdom|UK]].  Locations have included: [[Brussels]], [[Johannesburg]], [[Miami]], [[Moscow]], [[New York City|New York]], [[Paris]], [[Shanghai]], [[Sydney]], and [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/8220219.stm|title=Question Time from Brussels in June 1984|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/question_time/your_comments/474096.stm|title=Question Time from Sydney in October 1999|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2002/09_september/10/qt_12sep.shtml|title=Question Time from New York in September 2002|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/3963147.stm|title=Question Time from Miami in October 2004|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/4335687.stm|title=Question Time from Shanghai in March 2005|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/4584401.stm|title=Question Time from Paris in May 2005|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/4074774.stm|title=Question Time from Johannesburg in July 2005|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/4856290.stm|title=Question Time from Moscow in March 2006|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00f81tc|title=Question Time from Washington in October 2008|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Dimbleby hosted the final edition of his 25-year tenure in the ''Question Time'' chair. For this edition, the programme returned \"to where it all started in 1979\": ''Question Time'' was broadcast from the Greenwood Theatre, now part of [[King's College London GKT School of Medical Education|King's College London Medical School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kcl.ac.uk/news/News-Article.aspx?id=eedafa08-45bb-47fe-acbd-9999be488ed3|title=David Dimbleby hosts last BBC Question Time at King's|website=King\u2019s College London}}</ref>\n\n===Venues===\n''Question Time'' has filmed in notable buildings, including: the [[Scottish Parliament Building|Scottish Parliament]], the [[Senedd building|Welsh Assembly]], and [[Palace of Westminster#Westminster Hall|Westminster Hall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0bnb623|title=Question Time from the Scottish Parliament|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0008sd4|title=Question Time from the Welsh Assembly}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/oct/20/bbc-broadcast-question-time-parliament|title=BBC to Broadcast Question Time From Parliament for First Time in 32 Years}}</ref>\n\nIt has also broadcast from: [[Heathrow Airport]], [[HM Prison Wormwood Scrubs|Wormwood Scrubs Prison]], and the cathedrals of [[Liverpool Cathedral|Liverpool]] and [[St Paul's Cathedral|St Paul's]], [[Winchester Cathedral|Winchester]] and [[Worcester Cathedral|Worcester]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-27445732|title=Question Time filmed from Heathrow Airport, Wormwood Scrubs, St Paul's Cathedral, and Winchester Cathedral|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2002/10_october/01/qt_liverpool.shtml|title=Question Time broadcasts from Liverpool Cathedral|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worcesternews.co.uk/news/10381291.bbc-question-time-live-from-worcester-cathedral|title=Question Time from Worcester Cathedral|website=Worcester News}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, ''Question Time'' has been held in prestigious universities, including: [[Queen Mary University of London]], and the universities of [[University of Birmingham|Birmingham]] and [[University of Nottingham|Nottingham]], [[University of Sheffield|Sheffield]] and [[University of York|York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qmhospitality.co.uk/about/news/2014news/items/qms-octagon-takes-time-out-for-questions.html|title=Question Time in London}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.birmingham.ac.uk/news/latest/2008/10/1Oct-Question.aspx|title=Question Time at University of Birmingham}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/news/nottingham-news/best-programme-ages-twitter-reacts-2798826|title=Twitter reacts to Question Time in Nottingham}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theneweuropean.co.uk/top-stories/who-is-on-the-bbc-question-time-panel-in-sheffield-tonight-march-28-2019-1-5964044|title=Who is on the BBC Question Time panel tonight?}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.york.ac.uk/news-and-events/features/question-time|title=Question Time at the University of York}}</ref>\n\nOther venues have included:\n{{div col|colwidth=17em}}\n* [[Aberystwyth University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aber.ac.uk/en/news/archive/2011/11/title-109568-en.html|title=Question Time from Aberystwyth University|website=Aberystwyth University}}</ref>\n* Nottingham's [[Albert Hall, Nottingham|Albert Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/15/michael-gove-on-question-times-eu-referendum-special-the-verdict|title=Michael Gove on Question Time's EU referendum special from Nottingham|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n* Basingstoke's [[The Anvil, Basingstoke|Anvil Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basingstokegazette.co.uk/news/10760324.topical-debate-as-question-time-visits-the-anvil/|title=Topical debate as Question Time visits The Anvil|website=Basingstoke Gazette}}</ref>\n* [[Aylesbury Waterside Theatre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buckinghamtoday.co.uk/news/bbc-s-question-time-comes-to-aylesbury-1-8796359|title=BBC's Question Time comes to Aylesbury|website=Buckingham and Winslow Advertiser}}</ref>\n* the [[Barbican Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/22974284d4674d1792c979b4da193591|title=Question Time from the Barbican Centre|website=BBC}}</ref>\n* Aberdeen's [[Beach Ballroom]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/news/local/bbcs-question-time-aired-aberdeen-tonight|title=BBC\u2019s Question Time to be aired from Aberdeen tonight|website=Evening Express}}</ref>\n* [[Bishop Auckland Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theneweuropean.co.uk/top-stories/who-is-on-the-bbc-question-time-panel-in-bishop-auckland-tonight-september-27-2018-1-5713703|title=Question Time from Bishop Auckland|website=The New European}}</ref>\n* [[Bishop's Stortford College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bishopsstortfordcollege.org/206/latest-news/post/719/question-time-airs-from-the-college|title=Question Time airs from the College|website=Bishop's Stortford College}}</ref>\n* Dundee's [[Caird Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/question-time-audience-against-snp-claim-independence-supporters-1-4062166|title=Question Time from Dundee|website=The Scotsman}}</ref>\n* the [[CBSO Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cbso.co.uk/inside-cbso-centre|title=Question Time from Birmingham|website=CBSO Centre}}</ref>\n* [[Chester Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chestertownhall.co.uk/stories/44/question-time-comes-to-chester-town-hall|title=Question Time comes to Chester Town Hall|website=Chester Town Hall}}</ref>\n* London's [[City Hall, London|City Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2013/qt-brand|title=Question Time from London\u2019s City Hall|website=BBC}}</ref>\n* Southend's [[Cliffs Pavilion]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chelmsfordweeklynews.co.uk/news/14881017._All_hail_purple_jumper_man____TV_viewers__glee_at_outspoken_audience_member_as_BBC_Question_Time_comes_to_Southend|title=BBC Question Time comes to Southend|website=Chelmsford Weekly News}}</ref>\n* [[Coventry University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/tv/bbc-question-time-panel-tonights-13190037|title=BBC Question Time from Coventry|website=Coventry Telegraph}}</ref>\n* Bexhill's [[De La Warr Pavilion]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/schools_question_time/8908991.stm|title=Question Time 2010|website=BBC}}</ref>\n* [[Dewsbury Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.examinerlive.co.uk/news/tv/heres-your-chance-join-question-14927533|title=Dewsbury Town Hall hosts Question Time|website=Examiner Live}}</ref>\n* Glasgow's [[Easterhouse]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2013/question-time-st-pauls.html|title=Easterhouse hosts Question Time|website=BBC}}</ref>\n* [[Edinburgh Corn Exchange]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theedinburghreporter.co.uk/2013/06/heated-exchanges-on-question-time-from-edinburgh|title=Question Time from Edinburgh|website=The Edinburgh Reporter}}</ref>\n* [[Epsom College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.epsomcollege.org.uk/2019/05/epsom-college-to-host-bbc-question-time|title=Epsom College to host BBC Question Time|website=Epsom College}}</ref>\n* [[Glasgow Royal Concert Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://glasgowvenuehire.org.uk/pages/venue-details.aspx?vid=9|title=Question Time from Glasgow Royal Concert Hall|website=Glasgow Venue Hire}}</ref>\n* Wrexham's [[Wrexham Glynd\u0175r University|Glynd\u0175r University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/alan-johnson-bbc-question-time-2693748|title=Question Time from Wrexham|website=The Daily Post}}</ref>\n* [[Guildford High School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guildfordhigh.surrey.sch.uk/Hosting-Question-Time|title=Hosting Question Time|website=Guildford High School}}</ref>\n* [[James Allen's Girls' School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jags.org.uk/news/2018-11-27/Question-Time-comes-to-JAGS|title=Question Time comes to James Allen's Girls' School|website=James Allen's Girls' School}}</ref>\n* [[Kettering Conference Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.northantstelegraph.co.uk/news/panellists-confirmed-for-question-time-s-kettering-visit-1-8480287|title=Question Time\u2019s Kettering visit|website=Northamptonshire Telegraph}}</ref>\n* [[Kingswood Secondary Academy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingswoodsecondaryacademy.org/news/default.asp?storyID=258&pid=2&nid=2|title=BBC Question Time|website=Kingswood Secondary Academy}}</ref>\n* [[Leeds Beckett University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leedsbeckett.ac.uk/news/0318-leeds-beckett-hosts-lively-question-time|title=Leeds Beckett hosts Question Time|website=Leeds Beckett University}}</ref>\n* [[Leeds Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leeds-live.co.uk/news/celebs-tv/bbc-explains-controversial-decision-under-14407314|title=Question Time visits Leeds Town Hall|website=Leeds Live}}</ref>\n* the [[Lincoln Drill Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-17154444|title=Question Time from Lincoln Drill Hall|website=BBC}}</ref>\n* [[St Luke Old Street|LSO St Luke's]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BoOXac0nitS|title=Question Time at LSO St Luke's|website=Instagram}}</ref>\n* Birmingham's [[mac (Birmingham)|MAC]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://macbirmingham.co.uk/hire/room/theatre|title=Question Time in Birmingham|website=mac Birmingham}}</ref>\n* the [[Marshall Arena]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.miltonkeynes.co.uk/news/prime-minister-visits-milton-keynes-for-special-edition-of-question-time-at-arena-mk-1-7439217|title=Prime Minister visits Milton Keynes for special edition of Question Time at arena:mk|website=MK Citizen}}</ref>\n* [[Middlesbrough Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.middlesbrough.gov.uk/news/any-questions-middlesbrough-town-hall|title=Question Time from Middlesbrough Town Hall|website=Middlesbrough Council}}</ref>\n* [[MidKent College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/news/galloway-and-starkey-head-to-head-on-12422/|title=Question Time at MidKent College|website=Kent Online}}</ref>\n* [[Northampton High School, England|Northampton High School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://northamptonhigh.co.uk/2019/05/bbc-question-time-hosted-by-northampton-high-school|title=BBC Question Time hosted by Northampton High School|website=Northampton High School}}</ref>\n* [[North Oxfordshire Academy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.banburyguardian.co.uk/whats-on/tv-and-film/bbc-question-time-coming-to-banbury-1-8579766|title=BBC Question Time coming to Banbury|website=Banbury Guardian}}</ref>\n* the [[Queen Elizabeth II Centre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/first-night-sure-footwork-from-dimbleby-question-time-bbc-television-1406768.html|title=Question Time from London|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n* [[Rochdale Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/magnificent-rochdale-town-hall-steals-6086868|title=\u2018Magnificent\u2019 Rochdale town hall steals show as BBC\u2019s Question Time comes to town|website=Manchester Evening News}}</ref>\n* the [[The Sage, Gateshead|Sage]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/bbc-question-time-recap-flagship-9438526|title=BBC Question Time from the Sage Gateshead|website=The Journal}}</ref>\n* Halifax's [[Square Chapel]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.squarechapel.co.uk/2019/06/question-time-comes-to-square-chapel-on-thursday-27-june|title=Question Time comes to Square Chapel|website=Square Chapel}}</ref>\n* [[Stamford School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stamfordmercury.co.uk/whats-on/bbc-question-time-to-be-filmed-at-stamford-school-1-7184910|title=BBC Question Time to be filmed at Stamford School|website=Rutland and Stamford Mercury}}</ref>\n* Norwich's [[St. Andrew's and Blackfriars' Hall, Norwich|St Andrew's Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.edp24.co.uk/news/politics/panel-spar-over-tax-avoidance-at-bbc-question-time-from-norwich-1-3954645|title=BBC Question Time from Norwich|website=Eastern Daily Press}}</ref>\n* Newbury's [[St Bartholomew's School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newburytoday.co.uk/news/news/12451/bbc-s-question-time-comes-to-newbury-tonight-thurs.html|title=BBC's Question Time comes to Newbury|website=Newbury Today}}</ref>\n* [[St Dunstan's College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stdunstans.org.uk/media/news/article/2003/Question-Time-is-coming-to-St-Dunstan-s-College|title=Question Time is coming to St Dunstan's College|website=St Dunstan's College}}</ref>\n* Milford Haven's [[Torch Theatre, Milford Haven|Torch Theatre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milfordmercury.co.uk/news/17005310.bbc-political-debate-programme-question-time-to-come-to-torch-theatre|title=Question Time to come to Torch Theatre|website=Milford Mercury}}</ref>\n* the [[University of Brighton]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brighton.ac.uk/about-us/news-and-events/news/2014/03-28_university-hosts-question-time.aspx|title=Brighton hosts Question Time|website=University of Brighton}}</ref>\n* the [[University of Chichester]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chichester.co.uk/news/politics/bbcqt-question-time-coming-to-chichester-1-8984968|title=Question Time coming to Chichester|website=Chichester Observer}}</ref>\n* the [[University of Plymouth]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.plymouth.ac.uk/news/question-time-is-broadcast-from-the-house|title=Question Time from University of Plymouth|website=University of Plymouth}}</ref>\n* the [[University of West London]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uwl.ac.uk/news-events/news/uwl-hosts-bbc\u2019s-question-time-0|title=UWL hosts BBC\u2019s Question Time|website=University of West London}}</ref>\n* Stirling's [[Wallace High School, Stirling|Wallace High School]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/wallacehighsch/status/799259968138518528|title=Question Time from Stirling|website=Twitter}}</ref>\n* [[Walsall Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/politics/2016/05/19/lib-dem-leader-on-panel-for-question-time-in-walsall|title=Question Time in Walsall|website=Express and Star}}</ref>\n* [[Weymouth College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/10157942.question-time-comes-to-weymouth|title=Question Time comes to Weymouth|website=Dorset Echo}}</ref>\n* Gravesend's [[Woodville Halls Theatre]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/gravesend/news/question-time-comes-to-gravesend-a84748|title=Question Time comes to Gravesend|website=Kent Online}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n===2020 locations===\nFuture locations and panellists sometimes change.  Updates to locations are listed on the ''Question Time'' website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006t1q9/episodes/guide|title=Previously held and forthcoming Question Time editions|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/send/u21723349?ptrt=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006t1q9|title=Forthcoming Question Time locations|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n{{div col|colwidth=17em}}\n* 9 January: [[Oxford]]\n* 16 January: [[Liverpool]]\n* 23 January: [[Stoke Newington]]\n* 30 January: [[Buxton]]\n* 6 February: [[Harpenden]]\n* 13 February: [[Dundee]]\n* 20 February: [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]]\n* 27 February: [[Middlesbrough]]\n* 5 March: [[Royal Tunbridge Wells|Tunbridge Wells]]\n* 12 March: [[West Bromwich]]\n* 19 March: [[Weston-super-Mare]]\n* 26 March: [[Shrewsbury]]\n* 2 April: [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Production===\nThe show is recorded at [[location shooting|different venues]] throughout the UK. Although, as part of plans to relocate BBC production around the UK, the main office of the programme will move to [[BBC Scotland]] in [[Glasgow]], the itinerant nature of the programme will continue.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/mar/24/newsnight-review-revamp BBC2's \"Newsnight Review to get revamp\",] ''The Guardian'', 24 March 2009.</ref>\n\n==Famous editions==\nIn early 1981, [[David Steel]] declared his support in principle for \"a marriage\" between the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] and any party which might be formed by the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)#Creation of the SDP|Gang of Four]]; [[David Owen]], who was also on the programme, said he could see advantages in an \"electoral alliance\" between them. This prefigured the period 1983\u20131987 when Owen and Steel were Leaders of the [[SDP-Liberal Alliance]] and tension grew over whether their deal was a prelude to a merger of the parties or merely a temporary electoral pact.\n\nDuring the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 election campaign]], [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[Francis Pym]] was asked by an A-level student named Andy Davis about the implications of the Conservatives winning the election with a landslide victory. He began by casting doubt on the likelihood of this happening and then observed \"I think landslides on the whole don't produce successful governments\". Margaret Thatcher later wrote that the remark \"struck a wrong note\": \"people drew the inference that he did not want us to win a large majority\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Thatcher |first=Margaret |title=The Downing Street Years |url=https://archive.org/details/downingstreetyea00that |url-access=registration |publisher=HarperCollins |year=1993 |page=[https://archive.org/details/downingstreetyea00that/page/n329 294] |ISBN=0002550490}}</ref> After the election (won by the Conservatives on a landslide) she sacked him as [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]], partly because of his [[gaffe]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Thatcher |first=Margaret |title=The Downing Street Years |url=https://archive.org/details/downingstreetyea00that |url-access=registration |publisher=HarperCollins |year=1993 |page=[https://archive.org/details/downingstreetyea00that/page/n341 306] |ISBN=0002550490}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1984 edition, [[Alan Clark]], a junior government Minister at the time, was openly critical of a government decision to buy a foreign-made missile system, prompting guest host [[Sue Lawley]] to ask the audience, \"Is there anyone here who wishes to defend the government on this, because its Minister doesn't?\"\n\nA 1994 edition was notable for a confrontation between [[Jeffrey Archer]] and the historian [[David Starkey]] over the age of homosexual consent. After arguing that 18 should be the age of consent, Archer was attacked by Starkey who told him: \"Englishmen like you enjoy sitting on the fence so much because you enjoy the sensation.\"<ref>{{Citation | last = Havard | first = Ed | title = Question Time defined by 'epic' battles | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/9366830.stm | publisher = news.bbc.co.uk | date = 20 January 2011 | accessdate = 16 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe programme broadcast on 13 September 2001, which was devoted to the political implications of the [[11 September 2001 attacks]], featured many contributions from members of the audience who were anti-American, expressing the view that \"the United States had it coming\". The BBC received more than 2,000 complaints and later apologised to viewers for causing offence, stating that the edition should not have been broadcast live, but rather should have been recorded and edited.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/1544897.stm BBC chief apologises for terror debate], BBC News, 15 September 2001</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the editor of ''[[Private Eye]]'', [[Ian Hislop]], made an open attack on Jeffrey Archer, who had been imprisoned for [[perjury]], when his wife [[Mary Archer]] was a fellow panellist. She was noticeably angry that the issue had been raised and criticised Hislop after the recording had finished.\n\nIn March 2007, an Iraq Special was broadcast, featuring [[Tony Benn]], [[Benazir Bhutto]], [[Des Browne]], [[Liam Fox]], [[Charles Kennedy]] and, via [[video link]] from [[Washington D.C.]], [[John R. Bolton]]. The episode is particularly memorable for the clashes between Benn and Bolton.\n\nOn 11 October 2007, former editor of ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' newspaper [[Kelvin MacKenzie]] appeared on the programme in [[Cheltenham]] and launched an attack on Scotland. During a debate about tax, MacKenzie claimed that \"Scotland believes not in entrepreneurialism like London and the south east... Scots enjoy spending it (money) but they don't enjoy creating it, which is the opposite to down south.\" The comments came as part of an attack on [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] who MacKenzie said could not be trusted to manage the British economy because he was \"a Scot\" and a \"socialist\", and insisting that this was relevant to the debate. Fellow panellist [[Chuka Umunna]] from the [[think tank]] Compass called his comments \"absolutely disgraceful\", and booing and jeering were heard from the Cheltenham studio audience. The BBC received 350 complaints and MacKenzie's comments drew widespread criticism in both Scotland and England. On 3 July 2008, it was reported that the BBC Trust's editorial complaints unit had cleared the programme of any wrongdoing. ''Question Time'' then proceeded to broadcast the following question from Nick Hartley as part of the programme on the same evening: \"After the media coverage of [Andy] Murray's rise and fall, are we now to infer that the English resent the Scots more than the Scots resent the English?\" MacKenzie reappeared on the programme in [[Cardiff]] on 17 May 2012.\n\nAfter he was elected to the European Parliament, [[Nick Griffin]] the leader of the [[British National Party]] was invited onto ''Question Time'' for the first time, to appear on 22 October 2009. The decision led to [[Question Time British National Party controversy|controversy and political debate]]. Hundreds of people protested outside [[BBC Television Centre]] as the edition was filmed; six people were arrested after 25 protesters forced their way into the main reception.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/2009/oct/22/bnp-question-time-live-buildup \"BNP on Question Time\",] ''The Guardian'', 22 October 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8321157.stm | work=BBC News | title=Angry scenes face Griffin at BBC | date=22 October 2009 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> The edition attracted eight million viewers,<ref name=BNPcontroversy>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8322322.stm|title= Griffin complaint over BBC 'mob'|publisher=BBC News|date= 23 October 2009|accessdate= 23 October 2009}}</ref> and also drew a large number of complaints as a result of its content. Griffin himself said that he would make a formal complaint to the BBC for the way he believed he was treated by the show's other guests and the audience, who he described as a \"lynch mob.\"<ref name=BNPcontroversy/>\n\nAn edition aired on 19 May 2011 was recorded at [[Wormwood Scrubs (HM Prison)|Wormwood Scrubs Prison]] in [[London]]. The episode was the first to feature prisoners as part of the audience, while panellists included [[Secretary of State for Justice|Justice Secretary]] [[Kenneth Clarke|Ken Clarke]] who attempted to defend controversial remarks he had made earlier in the week about rape sentencing.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/may/20/question-time-tv-ratings|title= Ken Clarke detains 3 million on Question Time|publisher= Guardian Media Group|work= The Guardian|first= Ben|last= Dowell|date= 20 May 2011|accessdate= 21 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nA special edition of the programme was aired on 11 August 2011 following the [[2011 England riots|outbreak of rioting]] which had occurred during the previous weekend and earlier that week.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/aug/12/question-time-riots-special|title= Question Time riots special draws 3.6m viewers|publisher= Guardian Media Group|work= The Guardian|first= Ben|last= Dowell|date= 12 August 2011|accessdate= 16 August 2011}}</ref> ''Question Time'' had been off air for its annual summer break at the time and the edition was a scheduled at short notice due to the English riots.\n\nAn [[Question Time George Galloway in Finchley controversy|appearance by George Galloway]] on the edition of 5 February 2015 recorded in Finchley gained much negative comment before the broadcast. Inviting Galloway, a politician who has been outspoken about Israel, onto the programme was thought to be provocative and insensitive because Finchley has a large Jewish minority.<ref name=\"Rashty\">Sandy Rashty [http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/129151/galloway-question-time-appearance-chance-call-mp-account-says-board \"Galloway Question Time appearance is chance to call MP to account, says Board\"], ''The Jewish Chronicle'', 29 January 2015</ref> Galloway, who was heckled during a discussion about antisemitism, thought he had been defamed by a question posed to him, which insinuated that he should share some of the blame for a rise in antisemitic incidents during 2014.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/feb/06/george-galloway-accuses-bbc-over-question-time-set-up \"George Galloway accuses BBC over Question Time 'set-up'\"], ''The Guardian'', 6 February 2015</ref>\n\nOn 23 November 2017, the programme was shortened because an audience member became ill and could not be safely moved.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42104904|title=Question Time cut short as woman falls ill|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 19th March 2020, the programme was broadcast for the first time without an audience in Weston-super-mare due to the Coronavirus outbreak. \n\nOn 26th March 2020, the programme moved to a semi-permanent home at the IMG Studios at Stockley Park in London as a measure to prevent unnecessary travel during the Coronavirus outbreak, the show followed a different format with no audience and the panellists sitting 2m apart to follow the social distancing regulations.\n\n==Audience figures==\nAudience figures for ''Question Time'' are usually around 2.7 million.{{Citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\nThe highest audience figures to date were recorded when Nick Griffin of the BNP appeared in an [[Question Time British National Party controversy|episode]] on 22 October 2009; the audience reaching 8.3&nbsp;million viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atvtoday.co.uk/8-million-watch-bnp-on-question-time/|title=8 Million Watch BNP on Question Time|website=ATV Today}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 May 2009, ''Question Time'' discussed the [[Disclosure of expenses of British Members of Parliament|MPs' expenses row]], with audience members heckling guest panellists [[Menzies Campbell]] and [[Margaret Beckett]], the Labour MP, who was booed by the audience for insisting that her expenses were her privilege. The TV audience reached 3.8&nbsp;million.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\n3.4&nbsp;million people watched in 2003 at the start of the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|war on Iraq]].\n\n==Similar programmes==\n* In 1994, [[BBC Scotland]] launched their own local debate show called ''Words with Wark'' which was broadcast on [[BBC One Scotland]] usually on the first Thursday of every month and this was presented by [[Kirsty Wark]]. The programme was axed in 1998.\n* Until 2010, [[BBC One Northern Ireland]] replaced ''Question Time'' with the more local debate show ''Let's Talk'' at least once a month hosted by Mark Carruthers, but this show has been axed and brought under the Spotlight brand. It is now shown once a month on Tuesday night with Noel Thompson. BBC One NI have their own political show called ''The View'': this is broadcast live from 10.35pm to 11.05pm, presented by Mark Carruthers, and is followed by ''Question Time''. If Question Time is made in Northern Ireland.\n* [[BBC World]] produces an Indian version of the programme for such viewers.\n* The Irish broadcaster [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]] produced a similar show, ''[[Questions and Answers (TV series)|Questions and Answers]]'', which ran from 1986 to 2009, and was replaced by ''[[The Frontline (Irish TV series)|The Frontline]]'', which is of a similar format.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2009/0814/1224252553041.html|title=Recession leaves its mark on RT\u00c9 schedule|date=14 August 2009|work=[[Irish Times]]|accessdate=12 September 2009}}</ref>\n* In March 2010, [[Dermot O'Leary]] hosted a spinoff edition of the show, which was broadcast on [[BBC Three]]. It was called ''First Time Voters' Question Time'', and the show was aimed at first time voters. This version of the programme was later commissioned on a permanent, monthly basis on BBC Three, to now be hosted by [[Richard Bacon (TV presenter)|Richard Bacon]], and re-titled ''Young Voters' Question Time''. He was replaced by [[Jake Humphrey]] then by [[Rick Edwards]] with [[Tina Daheley]], and the show was renamed ''Free Speech'' which goes out every month.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/09_september/21/question.shtml Young Voters' Question Time becomes permanent fixture on BBC Three] BBC Press Office, 21 September 2010</ref>\n*In 2007, the BBC commissioned ''[[The Big Questions]]'', a new programme with a similar format to ''Question Time'', which focuses on ethical and religious issues. It is broadcast on BBC One on Sunday mornings between 10{{nbsp}}am and 11{{nbsp}}am. Both programmes are produced by Mentorn Media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mentorn.tv/|title=MentornMedia|website=Mentorn Media}}</ref>\n* In 2008, the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] launched a similar, Australian version of the programme, called ''[[Q&A (Australian talk show)|Q&A]]''. Airing live weekly, it has become a critical success, achieving extremely positive ratings for the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] in Australia, with a wide audience from a range of demographics not all of which are normally noted for their interest in the Australian political scene.\n* In 2011, [[Azerbaijan]] launched its own version of the programme. ''[[Open Talk]]'' {{lang-az|A\u00e7\u0131q s\u00f6hb\u0259t}} is a weekly debate [[ANS TV]] television programme in Azerbaijan, based on ''Question Time''. The show features political leaders as well as other public figures. ''Open Talk'' is presented by [[Sevinj Osmanqizi]].\n\n===Schools edition===\nSeveral schools editions have been broadcast:\nOn 20 June 2005, with a panel of [[Tony Benn]], [[Justine Greening]], [[Lembit Opik]], [[June Sarpong]] and [[Otis Ferry]].<ref name=\"Classic Question Times\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/4549698.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Programmes - Question Time - Classic Question Times|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> On 6 July 2006, with a twenty-year-old student joining [[David Miliband]], [[Richard and Judy|Richard Madelely]], [[Sebastian Coe|Lord Coe]] and [[Julia Goldsworthy]].<ref name=\"Classic Question Times\"/>\nOn 5 July 2007, an 18-year-old student joined a panel of [[Ed Miliband]], [[Sayeeda Warsi]], [[Davina McCall]] and [[Douglas Murray (author)|Douglas Murray]].<ref name=\"Classic Question Times\"/> On 9 July 2009, one of the panellists was an eighteen-year-old student. Other panellists were [[Andy Burnham]], [[Jeremy Hunt (politician)|Jeremy Hunt]], [[Sarah Teather]] and [[Shami Chakrabarti]].<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00lp1wj ''Question Time, Schools Edition''], BBC One, 9 July 2009.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n===Other sources===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Bailey, Ric (26 January 2005) [http://news.bbc.co.uk/newswatch/ukfs/hi/newsid_4200000/newsid_4202800/4202877.stm \"NewsWatch: Question Time for Question Time\"] ''BBC News'' Retrieved 9 July 2005.\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/question_time/3869985.stm \"The Best of ''Question Time''\"]  ''BBC News'' Retrieved 9 July 2005.\n* Guyon, Janet (29 November 2001) [https://web.archive.org/web/20050206094842/http://www.mutualofamerica.com/articles/Fortune/2001_11_29/American.asp \"Fortune: The New Future\u2014The American Way\"] ''Mutual of America'' Retrieved 9 July 2005.\n* Shawcross, William (17 September 2001) [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2001/sep/17/september11.usa30 \"Stop This Racism\"] ''The Guardian'' Retrieved 9 July 2005.\n{{div col end}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0081t8r ''Question Time Extra'']\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01sfcms ''Question Time Extra Time'']\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episodes/b006t1q9/question-time BBC i